ategory:English male short story writers]]\n[[Category:English short story writers]]\n[[Category:English male novelists]]\n[[Category:English prisoners and detainees]]\n[[Category:Ghost story writers]]\n[[Category:People from Camden Town]]\n[[Category:People from Somers Town, London]]\n[[Category:Pseudonymous writers]]\n[[Category:People from Chatham, Kent]]\n[[Category:People from Portsmouth]]\n[[Category:Social critics]]\n[[Category:Victorian novelists]]\n[[Category:Writers from London]]\n[[Category:19th-century British short story writers]]\n[[Category:Members of the Athenaeum Club, London]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Arts]]\n", "name_user": "Jmcc150", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDeath:relevance of train crash", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_Dickens"}
{"title_page": "Barisan of Ibelin", "text_new": "{{Infobox noble|type\n| name              = Barisan\n| title             = \n| image             = Armoiries Ibelin.svg\n| caption           = Coat-of-arms of Ibelin.\n| succession        =\n| reign             = \n| predecessor       = \n| successor         = \n| spouse            = Helvis of Ramla\n| issue             = [[Hugh of Ibelin]]<br>[[Baldwin of Ibelin]]<br>[[Balian of Ibelin]]<br>Ermengarde<br>Stephanie\n| full name         = \n| titles            = \n| noble family      = [[House of Ibelin]]\n| house-type        = \n| father            = \n| mother            = \n| birth_name        =\n| birth_date        = \n| birth_place       =\n| death_date        = 1150\n}}\n'''Barisan of Ibelin''' ({{lang-fr|Barisan d'Ibelin}}; died 1150) was an important figure in the [[crusade]]r [[Kingdom of Jerusalem]], and was the founder of the [[Ibelin family]]. His name was later written as \"Balian\" and he is sometimes known as '''Balian the Elder, Barisan the Old''' or '''Balian I'''.  Barisan was [[Lordship of Ramla#Lords/officials of Ramla|lord of Ramla]] from 1138-1150.\n\nBarisan's origins are obscure. The Ibelins later claimed to be descended from the viscounts of Chartres, but according to [[Peter W. Edbury]], Barisan was probably from northern [[Italy]].<ref>Peter W. Edbury, ''John of Ibelin and the Kingdom of Jerusalem'' (Boydell Press, 1997), pg. 4.</ref> According to [[Jonathan Riley-Smith]], however, he may have indeed been connected to Chartres, as the brother of [[Hugh I of Jaffa|Hugh of Le Puiset]], [[Count of Jaffa]]; he would then have also been a cousin to the [[Montlh\u00e9ry]] family of King [[Baldwin II of Jerusalem]].<ref>Jonathan Riley-Smith, ''The First Crusaders, 1095-1131'' (Cambridge University Press, 1997), pp. 172-173.</ref>\n\nHowever, nothing certain is known of his life before 1115, when he appears as [[constable]] of Jaffa under Hugh. In 1120 he was present at the [[Council of Nablus]], where the first laws of the kingdom were promulgated, perhaps representing the new, underaged Count of Jaffa, [[Hugh II of Jaffa|Hugh II]].<ref>Riley-Smith, pg. 173.</ref> Around the same year, his services were rewarded with a marriage to [[Helvis of Ramla]], daughter of [[Baldwin I of Ramla]]. In 1134, when Hugh II rebelled against [[Fulk of Jerusalem|King Fulk]], Barisan supported the king, and soon became prominent at Fulk's court. In 1141, perhaps as a reward for his loyalty in 1134, he was granted the newly constructed castle of Ibelin, located in the County of Jaffa between [[Jaffa, Israel|Jaffa]] itself and the [[Fatimid]] [[Egypt]]ian fortress of [[Ashkelon|Ascalon]]. It was from this castle that the family took their name.<ref>Edbury, pg. 4.</ref>\n\nIn 1148 Barisan inherited the nearby lordship of [[Ramla]], through his wife Helvis.<ref>Edbury, pg. 5</ref> That year, Barisan was also present at the [[Council of Acre|council convened at Acre]] after the arrival of the [[Second Crusade]], at which it was decided to [[Siege of Damascus (1148)|attack Damascus]]. Barisan died in 1150 and Ibelin was inherited by Hugh. Helvis then married [[Manasses of Hierges]], [[Officers of the Kingdom of Jerusalem#Constables|Constable of Jerusalem]].<ref>Edbury, pg. 5.</ref>\n\nWith Helvis lady of Ramla (daughter of [[Baldwin I of Ramla]]), Barisan was the father of:\n* [[Hugh of Ibelin]], [[Lord of Ramla]]\n* [[Baldwin of Ibelin]], Lord of [[Mirabel (castle)|Mirabel]] and [[Lord of Ramla|Ramla]]\n* [[Balian of Ibelin|Barisan the Younger]] (known as Balian), [[Lord of Nablus]]\n* Ermengarde of Ibelin, [[Lord of Tiberias|Lady of Tiberias]], married [[William I of Bures]]\n* Stephanie of Ibelin (d. after 1167)\n\n==Sources==\n*[[William of Tyre]], ''A History of Deeds Done Beyond the Sea'', trans. E. A. Babcock and A. C. Krey. [[Columbia University Press]], 1943.\n*[[Peter W. Edbury]], ''John of Ibelin and the Kingdom of Jerusalem''. Boydell Press, 1997.\n*[[Jonathan Riley-Smith]], ''The First Crusaders, 1095-1131''. [[Cambridge University Press]], 1997, as Barisan the Old.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barisan of Ibelin}}\n[[Category:1150 deaths]]\n[[Category:Christians of the Crusades]]\n[[Category:House of Ibelin]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n[[Category:Lords of Ramla]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox noble|type\n| name              = Barisan\n| title             = \n| image             = Armoiries Ibelin.svg\n| caption           = Coat-of-arms of Ibelin.\n| succession        =\n| reign             = \n| predecessor       = \n| successor         = \n| spouse            = Helvis of Ramla\n| issue             = [[Hugh of Ibelin]]<br>[[Baldwin of Ibelin]]<br>[[Balian of Ibelin|Barisan the Younger]]<br>Ermengarde<br>Stephanie\n| full name         = \n| titles            = \n| noble family      = [[House of Ibelin]]\n| house-type        = \n| father            = \n| mother            = \n| birth_name        =\n| birth_date        = \n| birth_place       =\n| death_date        = 1150\n}}\n'''Barisan of Ibelin''' ({{lang-fr|Barisan d'Ibelin}}; died 1150) was an important figure in the [[crusade]]r [[Kingdom of Jerusalem]], and was the founder of the [[Ibelin family]]. His name was later written as \"Balian\" and he is sometimes known as '''Balian the Elder, Barisan the Old''' or '''Balian I'''.  Barisan was [[Lordship of Ramla#Lords/officials of Ramla|lord of Ramla]] from 1138-1150.\n\nBarisan's origins are obscure. The Ibelins later claimed to be descended from the viscounts of Chartres, but according to [[Peter W. Edbury]], Barisan was probably from northern [[Italy]].<ref>Peter W. Edbury, ''John of Ibelin and the Kingdom of Jerusalem'' (Boydell Press, 1997), pg. 4.</ref> According to [[Jonathan Riley-Smith]], however, he may have indeed been connected to Chartres, as the brother of [[Hugh I of Jaffa|Hugh of Le Puiset]], [[Count of Jaffa]]; he would then have also been a cousin to the [[Montlh\u00e9ry]] family of King [[Baldwin II of Jerusalem]].<ref>Jonathan Riley-Smith, ''The First Crusaders, 1095-1131'' (Cambridge University Press, 1997), pp. 172-173.</ref>\n\nHowever, nothing certain is known of his life before 1115, when he appears as [[constable]] of Jaffa under Hugh. In 1120 he was present at the [[Council of Nablus]], where the first laws of the kingdom were promulgated, perhaps representing the new, underaged Count of Jaffa, [[Hugh II of Jaffa|Hugh II]].<ref>Riley-Smith, pg. 173.</ref> Around the same year, his services were rewarded with a marriage to [[Helvis of Ramla]], daughter of [[Baldwin I of Ramla]]. In 1134, when Hugh II rebelled against [[Fulk of Jerusalem|King Fulk]], Barisan supported the king, and soon became prominent at Fulk's court. In 1141, perhaps as a reward for his loyalty in 1134, he was granted the newly constructed castle of Ibelin, located in the County of Jaffa between [[Jaffa, Israel|Jaffa]] itself and the [[Fatimid]] [[Egypt]]ian fortress of [[Ashkelon|Ascalon]]. It was from this castle that the family took their name.<ref>Edbury, pg. 4.</ref>\n\nIn 1148 Barisan inherited the nearby lordship of [[Ramla]], through his wife Helvis.<ref>Edbury, pg. 5</ref> That year, Barisan was also present at the [[Council of Acre|council convened at Acre]] after the arrival of the [[Second Crusade]], at which it was decided to [[Siege of Damascus (1148)|attack Damascus]]. Barisan died in 1150 and Ibelin was inherited by Hugh. Helvis then married [[Manasses of Hierges]], [[Officers of the Kingdom of Jerusalem#Constables|Constable of Jerusalem]].<ref>Edbury, pg. 5.</ref>\n\nWith Helvis lady of Ramla (daughter of [[Baldwin I of Ramla]]), Barisan was the father of:\n* [[Hugh of Ibelin]], [[Lord of Ramla]]\n* [[Baldwin of Ibelin]], Lord of [[Mirabel (castle)|Mirabel]] and [[Lord of Ramla|Ramla]]\n* [[Balian of Ibelin|Barisan the Younger]] (known as Balian), [[Lord of Nablus]]\n* Ermengarde of Ibelin, [[Lord of Tiberias|Lady of Tiberias]], married [[William I of Bures]]\n* Stephanie of Ibelin (d. after 1167)\n\n==Sources==\n*[[William of Tyre]], ''A History of Deeds Done Beyond the Sea'', trans. E. A. Babcock and A. C. Krey. [[Columbia University Press]], 1943.\n*[[Peter W. Edbury]], ''John of Ibelin and the Kingdom of Jerusalem''. Boydell Press, 1997.\n*[[Jonathan Riley-Smith]], ''The First Crusaders, 1095-1131''. [[Cambridge University Press]], 1997, as Barisan the Old.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barisan of Ibelin}}\n[[Category:1150 deaths]]\n[[Category:Christians of the Crusades]]\n[[Category:House of Ibelin]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n[[Category:Lords of Ramla]]\n", "name_user": "ArisMethymna", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barisan_of_Ibelin"}
{"title_page": "PartyNextDoor", "text_new": "{{short description|Canadian singer and songwriter from Toronto}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = PartyNextDoor\n| background       = solo_singer\n| image            = File:PartyNextDoor 2016 press photo.png\n| caption          = Braithwaite in 2016\n| birth_name       = Jahron Anthony Brathwaite\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1993|07|3}}<ref name=\"Schwartz, Danny\">{{cite web|last1=Delerme|first1=Felipe|title=Is This Proof That PartyNextDoor Has Been Lying About His Age for Years?|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/is-partynextdoor-actually-31-years-old-news.23092.html}}</ref>\n| birth_place      = [[Mississauga]], [[Ontario]], Canada\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Alternative R&B]]\n* [[Lo-fi music|lo-fi]]\n* [[chillwave]]\n* [[Ambient music|ambient]]\n* [[Hip hop music|hip hop]]\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n}}\n| occupation       = {{flatlist|\n* Singer\n* songwriter\n* rapper\n* record producer\n}}\n| years_active     = 2006\u2013present\n| label            = {{flatlist|\n* [[OVO Sound]]\n* [[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]]\n}}\n| associated_acts  = {{flatlist|\n* [[Cash Out]]\n* [[Drake (musician)|Drake]]\n* [[Halsey (singer)|Halsey]]\n* [[Jeremih]]\n* [[Preme]]\n* [[Supa Dups]]\n}}\n| website          = {{URL|http://partyomo.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Jahron Anthony Brathwaite''' (born July 3, 1993),<ref name=\"Schwartz, Danny\">{{cite web|last1=Delerme|first1=Felipe|title=Is This Proof That PartyNextDoor Has Been Lying About His Age for Years?|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/is-partynextdoor-actually-31-years-old-news.23092.html}}</ref> known professionally as '''PartyNextDoor''' (stylized in [[all caps]]), is a Canadian singer, songwriter, rapper and record producer.\n\nPartyNextDoor was the first artist signed to [[Drake (musician)|Drake]]'s [[OVO Sound]] [[record label]] in 2013<ref name=\"Coscarelli, Joe\">{{cite journal  |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/08/17/arts/music/partynextdoor-drake-rihanna-interview.html |title=PartyNextDoor Is Finding His Voice, and a Bigger Spotlight |work=[[New York Times]] |publisher=New York Times |location=New York |date=August 16, 2016 |accessdate=September 6, 2016 |author=Coscarelli, Joe}}</ref> and later that year released his first [[extended play|EP]] self-titled ''[[PartyNextDoor (EP)|PartyNextDoor]]''.<ref>{{cite journal  |url=http://www.complex.com/music/2013/05/listen-partynextdoor-wus-goodcurious |title=Listen: PartyNextDoor'Wus Good/Curious' |work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]] |publisher=Complex Media |location=New York |date=May 12, 2013 |accessdate=August 24, 2013 |author=Josephs, Brian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://rapfix.mtv.com/2013/07/01/drakes-ovo-signee-partynextdoor-drops-self-titled-debut/ |title=Drake's OVO Signee PartyNextDoor Drops Self-Titled Debut |publisher=[[MTV]] |date=July 1, 2013 |accessdate=August 24, 2013 |author=Alexis, Nadeska}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/singles/id.24793/title.PartyNextDoor+f.+Drake-Over+Here |title=PartyNextDoor f. Drake \u2013 Over Here |work=HipHopDX |publisher=Cheri Media Group |date=June 24, 2013 |accessdate=August 24, 2013}}</ref> He subsequently released ''[[PartyNextDoor Two]]'' and ''[[PNDColours]]'' in 2014 and ''[[PartyNextDoor 3]]'' in 2016. PartyNextDoor has collaborated with a number of artists, including [[Drake (musician)|Drake]], [[Big Sean]] and [[Jeremih]]. He has also seen success as a songwriter, having penned \"[[Work (Rihanna song)|Work]]\", which was released on [[Rihanna]]'s album ''[[Anti (album)|Anti]]'' and peaked at number-one on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], along with more songs such as \"[[Wild Thoughts]]\" which peaked at number 2 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.<ref name=\"Coscarelli, Joe\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/ogdenpayne/2016/11/21/inside-partynextdoors-ascent-from-chart-topping-songwriter-to-methodical-businessman/#61567e7a6b87|title=Inside PartyNextDoor's Ascent From Chart-Topping Songwriter To Methodical Businessman|last=Payne|first=Ogden|newspaper=Forbes|access-date=2017-01-22}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nJahron Anthony Brathwaite was born to a [[Jamaicans|Jamaican]] mother and a [[Trinidadians|Trinidadian]] father in [[Mississauga]], [[Ontario]], Canada.<ref name=\"Delerme, Felipe\">{{cite web|last1=Delerme|first1=Felipe|title=PartyNextDoor Speaks About his Music for the First Time|url=http://www.thefader.com/2015/04/21/partynextdoor-cover-story-interview|website=Fader|accessdate=28 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Musical career==\n===2007\u20132014: Career beginnings and debut album===\nHaving made [[Electronic music|electronic]]-infused [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] under his real name Jahron Brathwaite [Jahron B],  he signed a publishing deal with [[Warner/Chappell Music|Warner/Chappell]] as a songwriter, under the name PartyNextDoor, at age 18.<ref name=\"Delerme, Felipe\"/>{{failed verification|date=June 2018}} His first mixtape, ''[[PartyNextDoor (EP)|PartyNextDoor]]'', was released to the [[iTunes Store]] on July 1, 2013.<ref name=\"apple1\">{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/partynextdoor/id666647689 |title=PARTYNEXTDOOR by PARTYNEXTDOOR |work=[[iTunes Store]] |publisher=[[Apple Inc.|Apple]] |accessdate=August 24, 2013}}</ref> It entered on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Heatseekers Albums]] chart at number six with sales of 2,000 copies<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-juice/1569442/chance-the-rapper-partynextdoor-chart-with-free-mixtapes |title=Chance the Rapper, PARTYNEXTDOOR Chart With Free Mixtapes |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] |location=New York |date=July 11, 2013 |accessdate=November 8, 2013 |author=Greenwald, David}}</ref> and peaked at number 34 on the [[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums]] chart for the week of July 20, 2013.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/charts/2013-07-20/r-and-b-hip-hop-albums |title=Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] |location=New York |date=July 20, 2013 |accessdate=November 8, 2013|url-access=subscription }}</ref> He performed background vocals on \"Own It\" and \"Come Thru\" from Drake's third studio album, ''[[Nothing Was the Same]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ca.complex.com/music/2014/07/partynextdoor-announces-new-album-release-date|title=PARTYNEXTDOOR Announces \"PARTYNEXTDOOR Two\" Release Date|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nHis debut studio album ''[[PartyNextDoor Two]]'' was released on July 30, 2014. The record featured singles like \"Thirsty\", \"FWU\", \"East Liberty\" and the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' charted \"[[Recognize (song)|Recognize]]\", featuring [[Drake (musician)|Drake]]. Later that year, on December 3, 2014, PartyNextDoor released the 4-track EP titled ''PNDColours'', with the follow up COLOURS 2, released in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ortiz|first1=Edwin|title=PARTYNEXTDOOR Shares Four New Songs and Reveals World Tour Dates|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2014/12/partynextdoor-world-tour-dates-and-four-song-package|website=Complex|accessdate=31 January 2015|date=3 December 2014}}</ref> In 2015, he produced three songs on Drake's ''[[If You're Reading This It's Too Late]]'': \"Legend\", \"[[Preach (Drake song)|Preach]]\" and \"Wednesday Night Interlude\".<ref name=\"Delerme, Felipe\"/>\n\nstream partymobile\n\n== Discography ==\n{{Main|PartyNextDoor discography}}\n\n* ''[[PartyNextDoor Two]]'' (2014)\n* ''[[PartyNextDoor 3]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[Partymobile]]'' (2020)<ref name=\"partymobile\">{{cite web |url=http://hiphop-n-more.com/2020/01/partynextdoor-new-album-partymobile-delayed-to-february/ |title=PARTYNEXTDOOR announces new album 'PARTYMOBILE'; delays it to February |work=HipHopNMore |date=January 29, 2020 |accessdate=January 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Year !! Awards 