don |isbn=978-0-7522-2477-0 |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Rubin |first=Steven Jay |title=The James Bond films: a behind the scenes history |publisher=Arlington House |location=Westport, Conn |year=1981 |isbn=978-0-87000-523-7 |ref=harv |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/jamesbondfilmsbe0000rubi }}\n* {{Cite book |last=Rubin |first=Steven Jay |title=The Complete James Bond Movie Encyclopedia|publisher=[[McGraw-Hill|McGraw-Hill Contemporary]]| location=New York |year=2002|isbn=978-0-07-141246-9|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |last= Simpson |first= Paul |title= The rough guide to James Bond|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BikCz7XZijEC|year=2002 |publisher=Rough Guides |location=London |isbn=978-1-84353-142-5|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Smith |first=Jim |title=Bond Films |year=2002 |publisher=Virgin Books |location=London |isbn=978-0-7535-0709-4 |ref=harv |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/bondfilms0000smit }}\n* {{Cite book|title=Das grosse James-Bond-Buch|first=Siegfried|last=Tesche|publisher=Henschel Verlag |location=Berlin|year=2002|language=German|isbn=978-3-89487-440-7 |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |editor-last=Yeffeth |editor-first=Glenn |title=James Bond in the 21st century: why we still need 007|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zpI5RbRwnd4C&lpg=PA3&dq=James%20Bond%20in%20the%2021st%20century%3A%20why%20we%20still%20need%20007&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q&f=false|publisher=BenBella Books|location= Dallas, Texas|year=2006 |isbn=978-1-933771-02-1 |ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{commons category|Dr. No}}\n* [http://www.screenonline.org.uk/film/id/455547/ ''Dr. No'']{{cbignore}} at [[BFI Screenonline]]\n* {{mojo title|drno|Dr. No}}\n* {{IMDb title|0055928|Dr. No}}\n* {{amg movie|14575}}\n* {{tcmdb title|id=73298}}\n* {{AFI film|id=22934|title=Dr. No}}\n* [http://www.mgm.com/#/our-titles/566/Dr.-No/ ''Dr. No''] at [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]]\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|dr_no|Dr. No}}\n\n{{James Bond films}}\n{{SPECTRE stories}}\n{{Terence Young}}\n{{Harry Saltzman|state=autocollapse}}\n\n{{good article}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dr. No (Film)}}\n[[Category:1962 films]]\n[[Category:1960s action films]]\n[[Category:1960s spy films]]\n[[Category:1960s thriller films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:Cold War spy films]]\n[[Category:Dr. No (film)| ]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about amputees]]\n[[Category:Films about terrorism]]\n[[Category:Films adapted into comics]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Terence Young]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Albert R. Broccoli]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Harry Saltzman]]\n[[Category:Films set in Jamaica]]\n[[Category:Films set in London]]\n[[Category:Films set on beaches]]\n[[Category:Films set on islands]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Jamaica]]\n[[Category:Films shot at Pinewood Studios]]\n[[Category:James Bond films]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Johanna Harwood]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Richard Maibaum]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Berkely Mather]]\n[[Category:United Artists films]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Eon Productions films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1962 James Bond film directed by Terence Young}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=December 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Dr. No\n| image          = Dr. No - UK cinema poster.jpg\n| alt            = In the foreground, Bond wears a suit and is holding a gun; four female characters from the film are next to him.\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster by [[Mitchell Hooks]]\n| director       = [[Terence Young (director)|Terence Young]]\n| producer       = [[Harry Saltzman]]<br>[[Albert R. Broccoli]]\n| screenplay     = [[Richard Maibaum]]<br>[[Johanna Harwood]]<br>[[Berkely Mather]]\n| based on       = {{Based on|''[[Dr. No (novel)|Dr. No]]''|[[Ian Fleming]]}}\n| starring       = [[Sean Connery]]<br>[[Ursula Andress]]<br>[[Joseph Wiseman]]<br>[[Jack Lord]]\n| music          = [[Monty Norman]]\n| cinematography = [[Ted Moore]]\n| editing        = [[Peter R. Hunt]]\n| studio         = [[Eon Productions]]\n| distributor    = [[United Artists]]\n| released       = {{Film date|df=yes|1962|10|5|United Kingdom}}\n| runtime        = 109 minutes\n| country        = United States<ref>{{cite web |title=Dr. No |url=https://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/moviedetails/22934 |website=AFI Catalog |publisher=American Film Institute |accessdate=16 December 2019}}</ref><br />United Kingdom\n| budget         = $1.1 million\n| gross          = $59.5 million\n| border         = yes\n}}\n\n'''''Dr. No''''' is a 1962 [[spy film]] directed by [[Terence Young (director)|Terence Young]]. It is based on the 1958 novel [[Dr. No (novel)|of the same name]] by [[Ian Fleming]]. Starring [[Sean Connery]], [[Ursula Andress]], [[Joseph Wiseman]], and [[Jack Lord]], it is the first film in the [[List of James Bond films|''James Bond'' series]], and was adapted by [[Richard Maibaum]], [[Johanna Harwood]], and [[Berkely Mather]]. The film was produced by [[Harry Saltzman]] and [[Albert R. Broccoli]], a partnership that continued until 1975.\n\nIn the film, [[James Bond filmography|James Bond]] is sent to [[Colony of Jamaica|Jamaica]] to investigate the disappearance of a fellow British agent. The trail leads him to the underground base of [[Julius No|Dr. No]], who is plotting to disrupt an early American space launch from [[Cape Canaveral Air Force Station|Cape Canaveral]] with a radio beam weapon. Although it was the first of the Bond books to be made into a film, ''Dr. No'' was not the first of Fleming's novels. ''[[Casino Royale (novel)|Casino Royale]]'' was the debut for the character; however, the film makes a few references to threads from earlier books. This film makes reference to later books in the series as well, such as the criminal organisation [[SPECTRE]], which was not introduced until the 1961 novel ''[[Thunderball (novel)|Thunderball]]''.\n\nProduced on a low budget, ''Dr. No'' was a financial success. While the film received a mixed critical reaction upon release, it has gained a reputation over time as one of the series' best instalments.<!-- DO NOT CHANGE THE SPELLING OF INSTALMENTS - this is an article written in British English and retains the correct spelling --> ''Dr. No'' also launched a genre of \"secret agent\" films that flourished in the 1960s. The film also spawned a [[Dr. No (comics)|comic book adaptation]] and [[Dr. No (soundtrack)|soundtrack album]] as part of its promotion and marketing.\n\nMany of the iconic aspects of a typical James Bond film were established in ''Dr. No'': the film begins with an introduction to the character through the [[Gun barrel sequence|view of a gun barrel]] and a highly stylised main title sequence, both of which were created by [[Maurice Binder]].<ref>{{cite episode |date=2 April 2020 |title=Spies |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/m000gwzj |series=Mark Kermode's Secrets of Cinema |series-link=Mark Kermode's Secrets of Cinema |network=BBC |station=BBC Four |series-number=2 |number=3 |time=13:26 |access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref> It also established the iconic \"James Bond\" theme music. [[Production designer]] [[Ken Adam]] established an elaborate visual style that is one of the hallmarks of the film series.\n\n== Plot ==\n<!-- ATTENTION! Before editing this section, please see WP:FILMPLOT for more information. Plot summaries, usually for films in popular franchises, are set between 400-700 words. This article is written is British-English, so be sure to see WP:ENGVAR before inverting certain grammar, like \"recognise\" for example. Thank you for your support. -->\n\nJohn Strangways, the British [[Secret Intelligence Service|MI6]] Station Chief in [[Colony of Jamaica|Jamaica]], and his secretary, Mary Trueblood, are ambushed and killed by a trio of assassins called the \"Three Blind Mice\". They steal documents related to \"Crab Key\" and \"Doctor No\". In response, [[M (James Bond)|M]], the head of MI6, instructs agent [[James Bond filmography|James Bond]] to investigate Strangways' disappearance and to determine whether it is related to his co-operation with the American [[Central Intelligence Agency]] (CIA) on a case involving the disruption of rocket launches from [[Cape Canaveral Air Force Station|Cape Canaveral]] by [[Radar jamming and deception|radio jamming]].\n\nOn his arrival at Kingston Airport, Bond is picked up by a chauffeur claiming to have been sent to take him to [[King's House, Jamaica|Government House]]. Bond determines him to be an enemy agent and, after having him evade a car pursuing them, bests him in a fight. Bond starts to interrogate the chauffeur, who kills himself with a [[cyanide]] capsule hidden in a cigarette.\n\nAt Strangways' house, Bond sees a photograph of a boatman with Strangways. Bond locates the boatman, named [[Quarrel (James Bond)|Quarrel]], whom he recognises as the driver of the car that followed him. Bond, after overpowering Quarrel and his friend Puss Feller, meets Quarrel's passenger, [[Felix Leiter]], a CIA agent on the same mission as Bond. The CIA has traced the radio jamming signal to Jamaica but has not determined its exact origin. Quarrel, who is assisting Leiter, reveals that he had been guiding Strangways around the nearby islands to collect mineral samples. He also mentions the reclusive Dr. No, the owner of Crab Key, an island rigorously protected against trespassers by an armed security force.\n\nIn Strangways' house, Bond finds a receipt from Professor R.J. Dent concerning rock samples. Bond meets Dent, who claims he [[wikt:assay|assayed]] the samples for Strangways and determined them to be ordinary rocks. Dent subsequently visits Dr. No, who expresses displeasure at Dent's failure to kill Bond, as well as by visiting him in daylight, and orders him to try again with a [[tarantula]], which is released into Bond's bedroom at night. Bond survives, kills the poisonous spider and sets a trap for Dent, whom he interrogates and kills.\n\nUsing a [[Geiger counter]], Bond detects [[radioactive]] traces in Quarrel's boat where Strangways' mineral samples had been. Bond convinces a reluctant Quarrel to take him to Crab Key. There Bond meets the beautiful [[Honey Rider|Honey Ryder]], dressed only in a [[White bikini of Ursula Andress|white bikini]], who is collecting shells. Ryder leads Bond and Quarrel inland to an open swamp contaminated by radiation. After nightfall, they are attacked by the \"dragon\" of Crab Key, which is, in reality, a [[flamethrower]]-equipped tank. In the resulting battle, Quarrel is incinerated and killed, while Bond and Ryder are kidnapped, decontaminated in Dr. No's lair, and rendered unconscious with drugged coffee.\n\nUpon waking, they are escorted to dine with Dr. No, a Chinese-German criminal scientist who has [[Prosthesis|prosthetic]] metal hands due to radiation exposure. He reveals that he is a former member of a Chinese crime [[Tong (organization)|Tong]], from whom he stole ten million dollars, and is now an operative of the secret organisation  [[SPECTRE]] ('''SP'''ecial '''E'''xecutive for '''C'''ounter-intelligence, '''T'''errorism, '''R'''evenge, and '''E'''xtortion), after being rejected by both the Americans and the Soviets. He plans to disrupt the [[Project Mercury]] space launch from Cape Canaveral with his radio beam. He tries to recruit Bond into SPECTRE but fails. After dinner, Ryder is taken away and Bond is beaten by the guards.\n\nBond is imprisoned in a holding cell but escapes by crawling through an air vent which is heated and then flooded. Disguising himself as a worker, he finds his way to Dr. No's control centre, which contains a nuclear [[pool reactor]]. As the American rocket lifts off, Bond overloads the reactor and knocks Dr. No into the reactor pool, killing him, as the scientist is unable to climb out due to his metal hands. Bond finds and frees Ryder, and the two escape the island in a boat as the entire lair explodes. After the boat runs out of fuel, they are rescued by Leiter, who arrives on a [[Royal Navy]] ship. As Bond and Ryder kiss, Bond lets go of the ship's tow rope.\n\n== Cast ==\n{{div col|colwidth=35em}}\n\n* [[Sean Connery]] as [[James Bond filmography|James Bond]], a British MI6 agent, codename 007.\n* [[Ursula Andress]] as [[Honey Ryder]], A local shell diver, making a living by selling Jamaican seashells to dealers in Miami.\n**Andress' spoken dialogue was dubbed by [[Nikki van der Zyl]]<ref name=\"Dr. No 1962 - Cast\">{{cite web|url=http://www.screenonline.org.uk/film/id/455547/credits.html|title=Dr. No (1962) \u2013 Cast|work=[[Screenonline]]|publisher=[[British Film Institute]]|accessdate=9 June 2011}}</ref>, and her singing voice was dubbed by [[Diana Coupland]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/6136408.stm|title=Actress Diana Coupland dies at 74|date=10 November 2006|accessdate=7 June 2011|work=BBC News}}</ref> Both were uncredited.\n* [[Joseph Wiseman]] as [[Julius No|Dr. Julius No]], a reclusive member of [[SPECTRE]]\n* [[Jack Lord]] as [[Felix Leiter]], a [[CIA]] operative sent to liaise with James Bond while he is in Kingston.\n* [[Bernard Lee]] as [[M (James Bond)|M]]: The head of the British Secret Service.\n* [[Anthony Dawson]] as Professor R.J. Dent, a geologist with a practice in Kingston, who also secretly works for Dr. No.\n* [[John Kitzmiller]] as [[Quarrel (James Bond)|Quarrel]], A [[Cayman Islands|Cayman Islander]] who was employed by John Strangways to secretly go to Crab Key to collect rock samples; he also worked with Felix Leiter before Bond's arrival.\n* [[Zena Marshall]] as Miss Taro, The secretary to Mr. Pleydell-Smith at Government House in Kingston. She is actually a double agent working for Dr. No.\n* [[Eunice Gayson]] as [[Bond girl|Sylvia Trench]], a woman who meets Bond during a game of [[Baccarat (card game)|Baccarat]] at the London club Le Cercle.\n**Gayson's voice was dubbed by Nikki van der Zyl.<ref name=\"Dr. No 1962 - Cast\" /> \n* [[Lois Maxwell]] as [[Miss Moneypenny]], the secretary to M.\n* [[Peter Burton]] as [[Q (James Bond)|Major Boothroyd]], the head of [[Q (James Bond)|Q-Branch]], Boothroyd is brought in by M to replace Bond's [[Beretta M1934]] with a [[Walther PPK]]. This was Burton's only appearance as Q.\n* Reginald Carter as Mr. Jones, a henchman of Dr. No who was sent to pick up 007 at the [[Palisadoes Airport]].\n* Yvonne Shima as Sister Lily, a prison warden working at Dr. No's lair.\n* Michel Mok as Sister Rose, another warden working at Dr. No's lair.\n* [[Marguerite LeWars]] as Annabel Chung, a photographer and one of Dr. No's operatives who trails Bond.\n*Louis Blaazer as Pleydell-Smith, Chief Secretary at [[King's House, Jamaica|Government House]] in Kingston.\n*[[Timothy Moxon]] as John Strangways, the head of the Kingston station for the MI6, murdered by Dr. No's henchmen, the 'Three Blind Mice'.\n**Moxon's dialogue was dubbed by [[Robert Rietti]].<ref name=\"Dr. No 1962 - Cast\" /> Neither Moxon nor Rietti were credited.\n{{div col end}}\n\nAdditional cast members include Lester Pendergast as Quarrel's friend Puss Feller, William Foster-Davis as Police Superintendent Duff, Dolores Keator as Strangways' personal assistant Mary Trueblood, and [[Anthony Chinn]] as Chen, one of No's lab technician impersonated by Bond. [[Byron Lee and the Dragonaires]] appear as themselves. [[Milton Reid]], who would later starred in [[The Spy Who Loved Me (film)|''The Spy Who Loved Me'']], appears as one of Dr. No's guards.\n\n== Production ==\nWhen [[Harry Saltzman]] gained the rights for the novel, he initially did not go through with the project. Instead, [[Albert R. Broccoli|Albert R. \"Cubby\" Broccoli]] wanted the rights to the novels and attempted to buy them from Saltzman. Saltzman did not want to sell the rights to Broccoli and instead, they formed a partnership to make the films. A number of Hollywood film studios did not want to fund the films, finding them \"too British\" or \"too blatantly sexual\".{{sfn|Pfeiffer|Worrall|1998|p=13}} Eventually the two received authorisation from [[United Artists]] to produce ''Dr. No'', to be released in 1962. Saltzman and Broccoli created two companies: [[Danjaq]], which was to hold the rights to the films, and [[Eon Productions]], which was to produce them.<ref name=\"Inside Dr. No documentary\"/> The partnership between Broccoli and Saltzman lasted until 1975 when tensions during the filming of ''[[The Man with the Golden Gun (film)|The Man with the Golden Gun]]'' led to an acrimonious split and Saltzman sold his shares of Danjaq to United Artists.<ref name=\"DNB: A. Brocc\">{{cite journal|last=Parkinson|first=David|title=Broccoli, Albert Romolo (1909\u20131996)|journal=[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]|date=Jan 2011|doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/63151|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/63151|accessdate=1 December 2012|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|location=Oxford}} {{subscription}}</ref>\n\nInitially Broccoli and Saltzman had wanted to produce the eighth Bond novel, 1961's ''[[Thunderball (novel)|Thunderball]]'', as the first film, but there was an [[Thunderball (novel)#Writing and copyright|ongoing legal dispute]] between the screenplay's co-author, [[Kevin McClory]] and Ian Fleming. As a result, Broccoli and Saltzman chose ''Dr. No'':{{sfn|Cork|Scivally|2002|p=29}} the timing was apposite, with claims that American rocket testing at Cape Canaveral had problems with rockets going astray.<ref name=\"Dodds 2005 266\u2013289\">{{cite journal|last=Dodds|first=Klaus|title=Screening Geopolitics: James Bond and the Early Cold War films (1962\u20131967)|journal=Geopolitics|year=2005|volume=10|issue=2|pages=266\u2013289|doi=10.1080/14650040590946584|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\nThe producers offered ''Dr. No'' to [[Guy Green (filmmaker)|Guy Green]], [[Guy Hamilton]], [[Val Guest]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Rigby|first=Jonathan|title=Interview with Val Guest|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/features/interviews/guest.html|work=NFT Interviews|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629070237/http://www.bfi.org.uk/features/interviews/guest.html|archivedate=29 June 2011|publisher=[[British Film Institute]]|accessdate=7 June 2011}}</ref> and [[Ken Hughes]] to direct, but all of them turned it down. They finally signed [[Terence Young (director)|Terence Young]] who had a long background with Broccoli's [[Warwick Films]] as the director. Broccoli and Saltzman felt that Young would be able to make a real impression of James Bond and transfer the essence of the character from book to film. Young imposed many stylistic choices for the character which continued throughout the film series.<ref name=\"Inside Dr. No documentary\"/> Young also decided to inject much humour, as he considered that \"a lot of things in this film, the sex, and violence, and so on if played straight, a) would be objectionable, and b) we're never gonna go past the censors; but the moment you [[Taking the piss|take the mickey out]], put the [[tongue-in-cheek|tongue out in the cheek]], it seems to disarm.\"<ref>{{cite video|last=Young|first=Terence|authorlink=Terence Young (director)|title=Audio commentary |location=Dr. No (Ultimate Edition, 2006) |year=1999|medium=DVD |publisher=[[MGM Home Entertainment]]}}</ref>\n\nThe producers asked United Artists for financing, but the studio would only put up $1 million. Later, the UK arm of United Artists provided an extra $100,000 to create the climax where Dr. No's base explodes.<ref name=\"comm\"/> As a result of the low budget, only one [[Sound editor (filmmaking)|sound editor]] was hired (normally there are two, for sound effects and dialogue),<ref>{{cite video|people=Wanstall, Norman |title=Audio commentary|location=Dr. No (Ultimate Edition, 2006)|year=1999 |medium=DVD |publisher=[[MGM Home Entertainment]]}}</ref> and many pieces of scenery were made in cheaper ways, with M's office featuring cardboard paintings and a door covered in a leather-like plastic, the room where Dent meets Dr. No costing only \u00a3745 to build,<ref>{{cite video|authorlink=Ken Adam|last=Adam|first=Ken|title=Audio commentary|location=Dr. No (Ultimate Edition, 2006)|year=1999|medium=DVD |publisher=[[MGM Home Entertainment]]}}</ref> and the aquarium in Dr. No's base being magnified stock footage of goldfish.<ref name=drill/> Furthermore, when art director [[Syd Cain]] found out his name was not in the credits, Broccoli gave him a golden pen to compensate, saying that he did not want to spend money making the credits again.<ref>{{cite video|authorlink=Syd Cain|last=Cain|first=Syd|title=Audio commentary|location=From Russia With Love (Ultimate Edition, 2006)|year=1999|medium=DVD |publisher=[[MGM Home Entertainment]]}}</ref> Production designer [[Ken Adam]] later told UK daily newspaper ''[[The Guardian]]'' in 2005: \n\n<blockquote>The budget for ''Dr No'' was under $1m for the whole picture. My budget was \u00a314,500. I filled three stages at Pinewood full of sets while they were filming in Jamaica. It wasn't a real aquarium in Dr. No's apartment. It was a disaster to tell you the truth because we had so little money. We decided to use a rear-projection screen and get some stock footage of fish. What we didn't realise was because we didn't have much money the only stock footage they could buy was of goldfish-sized fish, so we had to blow up the size and put a line in the dialogue with Bond talking about the magnification. I didn't see any reason why Dr. No shouldn't have good taste so we mixed contemporary furniture and antiques. We thought it would be fun for him to have some stolen art so we used Goya's [[Portrait of the Duke of Wellington]], which was still missing at the time. I got hold of a slide from the National Gallery - this was on the Friday, shooting began on the Monday - and I painted a Goya over the weekend. It was pretty good so they used it for publicity purposes but, just like the real one, it got stolen while it was on display.<ref name=\"The Guardian 17 September 2005\">{{cite news |last= Dee |first= Johnny |title= Licensed to drill |url= https://www.theguardian.com/film/2005/sep/17/culture.features| date= 17 September 2005 |newspaper= [[The Guardian]] |location=London| accessdate=10 March 2016 }}</ref></blockquote>\n\n=== Writing ===\nBroccoli had originally hired [[Richard Maibaum]] and his friend [[Wolf Mankowitz]] to write ''Dr. No''{{'}}s screenplay, partly because of Mankowitz's help in brokering the deal between Broccoli and Saltzman.{{Sfn|Broccoli|1998|p=158}} An initial draft of the screenplay was rejected because the scriptwriters had made the villain, Dr. No, a monkey.{{Sfn|Broccoli|1998|p=159}}{{sfn|Smith|2002|p=19}} Mankowitz left the film, and Maibaum then undertook a second version of the story, more closely in line with the novel. Mankowitz eventually had his name removed from the credits after viewing early rushes, as he feared it would be a disaster.<ref name=\"Inside Dr. No documentary\" /> [[Johanna Harwood]] and thriller writer [[Berkely Mather]] then worked on Maibaum's script.{{sfn| McGilligan |1986|p=286}} Terence Young described Harwood as a [[script doctor]] who helped put elements more in tune with a British character.<ref name=comm/> Harwood stated in an interview in a ''Cinema Retro'' special on the making of the film that she had been a screenwriter of several of Harry Saltzman's projects; she claimed both her screenplays for ''Dr. No'' and her screenplay for ''From Russia with Love'' had followed Fleming's novels closely.<ref>''Johanna Harwood Interview'' ''Movie Classics # 4'' Solo Publishing 2012</ref>\n\nDuring the series' decades-long history only a few of the films have remained substantially true to their source material; ''Dr. No'' has many similarities to the novel and follows its basic plot, but there are a few notable omissions. Major elements from the novel that are missing from the film include Bond's fight with a [[giant squid]], and the escape from Dr. No's complex using the dragon-disguised swamp buggy. Elements of the novel that were significantly changed for the film include the use of a (non-venomous) tarantula spider instead of a [[centipede]]; Dr. No's secret complex being disguised as a [[bauxite]] mine instead of a [[guano]] quarry; Dr. No's plot to disrupt [[NASA]] space launches from Cape Canaveral using a radio beam instead of disrupting US missile testing on Turks Island; the method of Dr. No's death by boiling in overheating [[nuclear reactor|reactor]] coolant rather than a burial under a chute of guano, and the introduction of SPECTRE, an organisation absent from the book.{{sfn|Smith|2002|p=19}} Components absent from the novel but added to the film include the introduction of the Bond character in a gambling casino, the introduction of Bond's semi-regular girlfriend Sylvia Trench, a fight scene with an enemy chauffeur, a fight scene to introduce Quarrel, the seduction of Miss Taro, Bond's recurring CIA ally Felix Leiter, Dr. No's partner in crime Professor Dent and Bond's controversial cold-blooded killing of this character.{{sfn|Smith|2002|p=19}}\n\nSometimes episodes in the novel retained in the film's altered narrative introduce elements of absurdity into the plot. Bond's \"escape\" from his cell via the air shaft, for instance, originally conceived as a ruse of Dr. No's to test Bond's skill and endurance, becomes an authentic break-out in the film. Features carried over from the novel's obstacle course, however, such as the torrent of water and scalding surface, have no logical justification in the script. Such incongruities recurred in subsequent Bond films.{{sfn|Smith|2002|p=19}}\n\n=== Casting ===\n\n==== James Bond ====\nWhile producers Broccoli and Saltzman originally sought [[Cary Grant]] for the role, they discarded the idea as Grant would be committed to only one feature film, and the producers decided to go after someone who could be part of a series.<ref name=\"Inside Dr. No documentary\"/> [[Richard Johnson (actor)|Richard Johnson]] has claimed to have been the first choice of the director, but he turned it down because he already had a contract with MGM and was intending to leave.<ref>{{cite web|title=Richard Johnson Interview|url=http://www.cinemaretro.com/index.php?/archives/1524-RICHARD-JOHNSON-ON-DECLINING-THE-ROLE-OF-JAMES-BOND.html|work=[[Cinema Retro]]|accessdate=13 June 2011}}</ref> Another actor purported to have been considered for the role was [[Patrick McGoohan]] on the strength of his portrayal of spy [[John Drake (Danger Man)|John Drake]] in the television series ''[[Danger Man]]'': McGoohan turned down the role.<ref>{{cite news|last=Barker|first=Dennis|title=Obituary: Patrick McGoohan|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2009/jan/14/television2|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|location=London|date=14 January 2009}}</ref> Another potential Bond included [[David Niven]], who played the character in the 1967 parody ''[[Casino Royale (1967 film)|Casino Royale]]''.{{sfn|Macintyre|2008|p=202}}\n\nThere are several [[wikt:apocryphal|apocryphal]] stories as to whom Ian Fleming personally wanted. Reportedly, Fleming favoured actor [[Richard Todd]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Richard Todd, Obituary|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/culture-obituaries/film-obituaries/6725717/Richard-Todd.html|accessdate=8 June 2011|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|location=London|date=4 December 2009}}</ref> In his autobiography ''When the Snow Melts'', Cubby Broccoli said [[Roger Moore]] had been considered, but had been thought \"too young, perhaps a shade too pretty.\"{{Sfn|Broccoli|1998|p=165}} In his autobiography, ''My Word Is My Bond'', Moore says he was never approached to play the role of Bond until 1973, for ''[[Live and Let Die (film)|Live and Let Die]]''.{{Sfn|Moore|2008|p=173}} Moore appeared as [[Simon Templar]] on the television series ''[[The Saint (TV series)|The Saint]]'', airing in the United Kingdom for the first time on 4 October 1962, only one day before the premiere of ''Dr. No''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Clark|first=Anthony|title=Saint, The (1962\u201369)|url=http://www.screenonline.org.uk/tv/id/508296/index.html|work=[[Screenonline]]|publisher=[[British Film Institute]]|accessdate=15 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nUltimately, the producers turned to 32 year-old [[Sean Connery]] for five films.<ref name=\"Inside Dr. No documentary\"/> It is often reported that Connery won the role through a contest set up to \"find James Bond\". While this is untrue, the contest itself did exist, and six finalists were chosen and screen-tested by Broccoli, Saltzman, and Fleming. The winner of the contest was a 28-year-old model named Peter Anthony, who, according to Broccoli, had a [[Gregory Peck]] quality, but proved unable to cope with the role.{{sfn|Cork|Scivally|2002|p=31}} When Connery was invited to meet Broccoli and Saltzman he appeared scruffy and in unpressed clothes, but Connery \"put on an act and it paid off\" as he acted in the meeting with a macho, devil-may-care attitude.{{Sfn|Bray|2010|p=73}} When he left both Saltzman and Broccoli watched him through the window as he went to his car, both agreeing that he was the right man for Bond.{{Sfn|Bray|2010|p=74}} After Connery was chosen, Terence Young took the actor to his tailor and hairdresser,<ref name=gayson>{{cite video|last=Gayson|first=Eunice|authorlink=Eunice Gayson|title=Audio commentary|location=Dr. No (Ultimate Edition, 2006) |medium=DVD|year=1999 |publisher=[[MGM Home Entertainment]]}}</ref> and introduced him to the high life, restaurants, casinos and women of London. In the words of Bond writer [[Raymond Benson]], Young educated the actor \"in the ways of being dapper, witty, and above all, cool\".<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Benson|first=Raymond|author-link=Raymond Benson|title=Can the Cinematic Bond Ever Be the Literary Bond? |page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=zpI5RbRwnd4C&pg=PA7 7]|ref=harv}}. In {{harvnb|Yeffeth|2006}}.</ref>\n\n==== Secondary cast ====\nFor the first [[Bond girl]] Honey Ryder, [[Julie Christie]] was considered, but discarded as the producers felt she was not [[voluptuous]] enough.{{sfn|Lisanti|Paul|2002|p=36}} Just two weeks before filming began, Ursula Andress was chosen to play Honey after the producers saw a picture of her taken by Andress' then-husband [[John Derek]]. To appear more convincing as a Jamaican, Andress had a tan painted on her and ultimately had her lines redubbed by voice actress [[Nikki van der Zyl]] due to Andress' heavy Swiss-German accent.<ref name=\"Inside Dr. No documentary\"/> For Bond's antagonist Dr. No, Ian Fleming wanted his friend [[No\u00ebl Coward]], and Coward answered the invitation with \"No! No! No!\"{{sfn|Pfeiffer|Worrall|1998|p=16}} Fleming considered that his step-cousin, [[Christopher Lee]], would be good for the role of Dr. No, although, by the time Fleming told the producers, they had already chosen [[Joseph Wiseman]] for the part.<ref name=TFInterview>{{Cite news|url=http://www.totalfilm.com/features/the_total_film_interview__christopher_lee |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070612192345/http://www.totalfilm.com/features/the_total_film_interview__christopher_lee |archivedate=12 June 2007 |title=The Total Film Interview \u2013 Christopher Lee |work=Total Film |date=1 May 2005 |accessdate=28 January 2014}}</ref> Harry Saltzman picked Wiseman because of his performance in the 1951 film ''[[Detective Story (1951 film)|Detective Story]]'',<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/joseph-wiseman-actor-of-stage-and-screen-who-played-the-title-role-in-the-1962-james-bond-movie-dr-no-1810038.html|title=Joseph Wiseman: Actor of stage and screen who played the title role in the 1962 James Bond movie 'Dr. No'|date=27 October 2009|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|location=London}}</ref> and the actor had special make-up applied to evoke No's Chinese heritage.<ref name=\"Inside Dr. No documentary\"/>\n\nThe role as the first Felix Leiter was given to [[Jack Lord]]. This is Bond and Leiter's first time meeting each other on film and Leiter does not appear in the novel. Leiter returns for many of Bond's future adventures and in the 2006 reboot of the film series, ''[[Casino Royale (2006 film)|Casino Royale]]'', Leiter and Bond are seen meeting one another again for the first time. This was Lord's only appearance as Leiter, as he asked for more money and a better [[Billing (filmmaking)|billing]] to return as Leiter in ''[[Goldfinger (film)|Goldfinger]]'' and was subsequently replaced.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Goldberg|first=Lee|title=The Richard Maibaum Interview|journal=[[Starlog]]|date=March 1983|issue=68|page=26|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\nThe cast also included a number of actors who were to become stalwarts of the future films, including [[Bernard Lee]], who played Bond's superior M for another ten films, and [[Lois Maxwell]], who played M's secretary Moneypenny in fourteen instalments of the series.<ref>{{cite web |title=Lois Maxwell, 80, an Actress Who Played in 14 \u2018Bond\u2019 Films, Dies |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/10/01/movies/01maxwell.html |website=nytimes.com |publisher=The New York Times Company |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref> Lee was chosen because of being a \"prototypical father figure\",{{sfn|Cork|Scivally|2002|p=38}} and Maxwell after Fleming thought she was the perfect fit for his description of the character.{{sfn| Rubin |2002|p=272}} Maxwell was initially offered a choice between the roles of Moneypenny or Sylvia Trench and opted for Moneypenny as she thought the Trench role, which included appearing in immodest dress, was too sexual.{{sfn|Smith|2002|p=15}}{{sfn|Pfeiffer|Worrall|1998|p=15}} [[Eunice Gayson]] was cast as Sylvia Trench and it was planned that she would be a recurring girlfriend for Bond throughout six films,<ref name=gayson /> although she appeared only in ''Dr. No'' and ''[[From Russia with Love (film)|From Russia with Love]]''. She had been given the part by director Terence Young, who had worked with her in ''[[Zarak]]'' and invited Gayson saying \"You always bring me luck in my films\",{{sfn|Cork|d'Abo|2003|p=21}} although she was also cast due to her voluptuous figure. One role which was not given to a future regular was that of Major Boothroyd, the head of Q-Branch, which was given to Peter Burton. Burton was unavailable for the subsequent film, ''From Russia with Love'', and the role was taken by [[Desmond Llewelyn]].{{sfn|Simpson|2002|p=83}}\n\nAnthony Dawson, who played Professor Dent, met director Terence Young when he was working as a stage actor in London, but by the time of the film's shooting Dawson was working as a pilot and crop duster in Jamaica.<ref name=\"comm\"/> Dawson also portrayed [[Ernst Stavro Blofeld]], head of SPECTRE, in ''From Russia with Love'' and ''[[Thunderball (film)|Thunderball]]'', although his face was never seen and his voice was redubbed by Austrian actor [[Eric Pohlmann]].{{sfn|Smith|2002|p=30}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Thunderball (1965)|url=http://www.screenonline.org.uk/film/id/520479/credits.html|work=[[Screenonline]]|publisher=[[British Film Institute]]|accessdate=16 June 2011}}</ref> Zena Marshall, who played Miss Taro, was mostly attracted by the humorous elements of the script,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/obituaries/article6718273.ece|date=18 July 2009|title=Zena Marshall: actress in Dr No|work=[[The Times]]|location=London}}</ref> and described her role as \"this attractive little siren, and at the same time I was the spy, a bad woman\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Spotlight - Zena Marshall |url=https://www.thebondbulletin.com/spotlight-zena-marshall/ |website=thebondbulletin.com |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>, who Young asked to play \"not as Chinese, but a Mid-Atlantic woman who men dream about but is not real\".<ref>{{cite video|people=Marshall, Zena |title=Audio commentary|location=Dr. No (Ultimate Edition, 2006)|year=1999 |medium=DVD |publisher=[[MGM Home Entertainment]]}}</ref> The role of Taro was previously rejected by Marguerite LeWars, the Miss Jamaica 1961 who worked at the Kingston airport, as it required being \"wrapped in a towel, lying in a bed, kissing a strange man\".\n\n=== Filming ===\n[[File:Jamaica bauxite plant ocho rios 1975Dec 02b.jpg|right|thumb|Dr. No's lair was this bauxite terminal near Oracabessa, Jamaica]]\n''Dr. No'' is set in London, Jamaica and Crab Key, a fictional island off Jamaica.{{sfn|Cork|Scivally|2002|p=305}} Filming began on location in Jamaica on 16 January 1962. The primary scenes there were the exterior shots of Crab Key and Kingston, where an uncredited [[Syd Cain]] acted as [[art director]] and also designed the Dragon Tank.{{sfn|Cain|2005}} Shooting took place a few yards from Fleming's [[Goldeneye (estate)|Goldeneye]] estate, and the author regularly visited the filming with friends.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Nathan, Ian|title=Unseen Bond|work=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]|date=October 2008|page=97}}</ref> Location filming was largely in [[Oracabessa]], with additional scenes on the [[Palisadoes]] strip and [[Port Royal]] in [[Saint Andrew Parish, Jamaica|St Andrew]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Campbell|first=Howard|title=James Bond marathon begins with JA|url=http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/entertainment/James-Bond-marathon-begins-with-JA|newspaper=[[The Jamaica Observer]]|location=Kingston|date=17 June 2012}}</ref> On 21 February, production left Jamaica with footage still unfilmed due to a change of weather.<ref name=\"comm\">{{cite video|authorlink=John Cork|last=Cork|first=John|title=Audio commentary|location=Dr. No (Ultimate Edition, 2006)|year=1999|medium=DVD |publisher=[[MGM Home Entertainment]]}}</ref> Five days later, filming began at [[Pinewood Studios]], Buckinghamshire, England with sets [[production designer|designed]] by [[Ken Adam]], which included Dr. No's base, the ventilation duct and the interior of the British Secret Service headquarters. The studio was used on the majority of later Bond films.<ref name=\"Inside Dr. No documentary\">{{Cite video |year=1999 | title = Inside Dr. No Documentary |location=Dr. No (Ultimate Edition, 2006) |medium=DVD |publisher=[[MGM Home Entertainment]]}}</ref> Adam's initial budget for the entire film was just \u00a314,500 (\u00a3{{formatnum:{{Inflation|UK|14500|1962}}}} in {{inflation-year|UK}}{{inflation-fn|UK}}), but the producers were convinced to give him an extra \u00a36,000 out of their own finances. After 58 days of filming, principal photography completed on 30 March 1962.{{sfn|Rubin|1981|p=21}}\n\nThe scene where a tarantula walks over Bond was initially shot by pinning a bed to the wall and placing Sean Connery over it, with a protective glass between him and the spider. Director Young did not like the final results, so the scenes were interlaced with new footage featuring the tarantula over stuntman [[Bob Simmons (stunt man)|Bob Simmons]].<ref name=\"comm\"/> Simmons, who was uncredited for the film, described the scene as the most frightening stunt he had ever performed.{{sfn|Pfeiffer|Worrall|1998|p=17}} The book features a scene where Honey Ryder is tortured by being tied to the ground along with crabs, but since the crabs were sent frozen from the Caribbean, they did not move much during filming, so the scene was altered to have Honey slowly drowning.<ref name=\"Inside Dr. No documentary\"/> Simmons also served as the film's fight choreographer, employing a rough fighting style. The noted violence of ''Dr. No'', which also included Bond shooting Dent in cold blood, caused producers to make adaptations to get an [[History of British film certificates#1951\u20131970|\"A\" rating]] \u2013 allowing minors to enter accompanied by an adult \u2013 from the [[British Board of Film Classification]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Dr. No rated A by the BBFC |publisher=[[British Board of Film Classification]] |url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/website/Classified.nsf/c2fb077ba3f9b33980256b4f002da32c/a6d1a7459de40499802566c8002efa49?OpenDocument |accessdate=9 June 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120819182211/http://www.bbfc.co.uk/website/Classified.nsf/c2fb077ba3f9b33980256b4f002da32c/a6d1a7459de40499802566c8002efa49?OpenDocument |archivedate=19 August 2012 }}</ref>\n\nWhen he is about to have dinner with Dr. No, Bond is amazed to see [[Francisco Goya|Goya]]'s ''[[Portrait of the Duke of Wellington (Goya)|Portrait of the Duke of Wellington]]''. The painting had been stolen from the [[National Gallery]] by a 60-year-old amateur thief in London just before filming began.<ref>{{cite news|work=BBC News|title=Greatest heists in art history|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/arts/3590106.stm|date=23 August 2004}}</ref><!--This note is relevant since its basis is a current affair that is not widely known of today. It explains why Bond is so amazed to see that particular painting in Doctor No's residence.--> Ken Adam had contacted the National Gallery in London to obtain a slide of the picture, painting the copy over the course of the weekend, prior to filming commencing on the Monday.<ref name=drill>{{cite news|last=Dee|first=Johnny|title=Licensed to drill|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2005/sep/17/culture.features|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|location=London|date=17 September 2005}}</ref>\n\nEditor [[Peter R. Hunt]] used an innovative editing technique, with extensive use of quick cuts, and employing [[Time-lapse photography|fast motion]] and exaggerated sound effects on the action scenes.<ref>{{cite video|authorlink=Peter R. Hunt|last=Hunt|first=Peter R.|title=Goldfinger audio commentary|location=Goldfinger (Ultimate Edition, 2006), Disk 1|year=1999|publisher=MGM Home Entertainment}}</ref> Hunt said his intention was to \"move fast and push it along the whole time, while giving it a certain style\",<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://retrovisionmag.com/jamesbond.htm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090214005715/http://retrovisionmag.com/jamesbond.htm|archivedate=14 February 2009|title=Interview with Peter R. Hunt |publisher=Retrovision|issue=2|year=1997|ref=harv}}</ref> and added that the fast pacing would help audiences not notice any writing problems.<ref name=comm/> As title artist [[Maurice Binder]] was creating the credits, he had an idea for the introduction that appeared in all subsequent Bond films, the James Bond gun barrel sequence. It was filmed in [[Sepia tone|sepia]] by putting a [[pinhole camera]] inside an .38 calibre gun barrel, with Bob Simmons playing Bond.<ref name=\"Inside Dr. No documentary\"/> Binder also designed a highly stylised main title sequence, a theme that has been repeated in the subsequent Eon-produced Bond films.{{sfn|Cork|Scivally|2002|p=46}} Binder's budget for the title sequence was \u00a32,000 (\u00a3{{formatnum:{{Inflation|UK|2000|1962}}}} in {{inflation-year|UK}}{{inflation-fn|UK}}).<ref>{{cite journal|last=Kirkham|first=Pat|title=Dots and sickles|journal=[[Sight and Sound]]|location=London|date=December 1995|volume=5|issue=12|page=10|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\n== Soundtrack ==\n{{Main|Dr. No (soundtrack)}}\n[[Monty Norman]] was invited to write the soundtrack because Broccoli liked his work on the 1961 theatre production ''Belle'', a musical about murderer [[Hawley Harvey Crippen]].<ref name=\"theme\">{{cite web|url=http://www.montynorman.com/jamesbond/default.asp |title=The James Bond Theme History |publisher=Monty Norman official website |accessdate=28 March 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080309023538/http://www.montynorman.com/jamesbond/default.asp |archivedate=9 March 2008 }}</ref> Norman was busy with musicals, and only agreed to do the music for ''Dr. No'' after Saltzman allowed him to travel along with the crew to Jamaica.<ref name=Norman>{{cite video|authorlink=Monty Norman|last=Norman|first=Monty|title=Audio commentary|location=Dr. No (Ultimate Edition, 2006) |medium=DVD |publisher=[[MGM Home Entertainment]]}}</ref> The most famous composition in the soundtrack is the \"[[James Bond Theme]]\", which is heard in the gunbarrel sequence and in a calypso medley over the title credits, and was written by Norman based on a previous composition of his. [[John Barry (composer)|John Barry]], who would later go on to compose the music for eleven Bond films, arranged the Bond theme but was uncredited\u2014except for the credit of his orchestra playing the final piece. It has occasionally been suggested that Barry, not Norman, composed the \"James Bond Theme\". This argument has been the subject of two court cases, the most recent in 2001, which found in favour of Norman.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bond theme writer wins damages|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/1229406.stm|work=BBC News|date=19 March 2001}}</ref> The theme, as written by Norman and arranged by Barry, was described by another Bond film composer, [[David Arnold]], as \"bebop-swing vibe coupled with that vicious, dark, distorted electric guitar, definitely an instrument of rock 'n' roll&nbsp;... it represented everything about the character you would want: It was cocky, swaggering, confident, dark, dangerous, suggestive, sexy, unstoppable. And he did it in two minutes.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Burlingame|first=Jon|title=Bond scores establish superspy template|newspaper=[[Variety (magazine)|Daily Variety]]|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117995119?refcatid=3313&printerfriendly=true|date=3 November 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe music for the opening scene is a calypso version of the [[nursery rhyme]] \"[[Three Blind Mice]],\" with new lyrics to reflect the intentions of the three assassins hired by Dr. No.<ref name=\"theme\"/> Other notable songs in the film are the song \"Jump Up,\"{{sfn|Smith|2002|p=17}} played in the background, and the traditional Jamaican calypso \"Under the Mango Tree,\" famously sung by [[Diana Coupland]] (then Norman's wife), the singing voice of Honey Ryder, as she walked out of the ocean on Crab Key.<ref name=\"theme\"/> [[Byron Lee & the Dragonaires]] appeared in the film and performed some of the music on the later soundtrack album.{{sfn|Smith|2002|p=17}} Lee and other Jamaican musicians who appear in the soundtrack, including [[Ernest Ranglin]] and [[Carlos Malcolm]], were introduced to Norman by [[Chris Blackwell]], the owner of then-small label [[Island Records]] who worked in the film as a location scout.<ref name=Norman/>{{sfn|Burlingame|2012|p=10}} The original soundtrack [[Dr. No (soundtrack)|album]] was released by [[United Artists Records]] in 1963 as well as several [[cover version]]s of the \"[[James Bond Theme]]\" on [[Columbia Records]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Music \u2013 Dr No|url=http://www.mi6-hq.com/sections/movies/dn_music.php3|publisher=[[Mi6-HQ.com]]|accessdate=15 June 2011}}</ref> A single of the \"James Bond Theme\" entered the UK Singles Chart in 1962, reaching a peak position of number thirteen during an eleven-week spell in the charts.<ref>{{cite web|title=John Barry Seven|url=http://www.theofficialcharts.com/artist/_/john%20barry%20seven/|work=Official UK Charts Archive|publisher=The Official UK Charts Company|accessdate=30 June 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111011060342/http://www.theofficialcharts.com/artist/_/john%20barry%20seven/|archivedate=11 October 2011}}</ref> Ranglin, who had acted as arranger on several tracks, and Malcolm sued Eon for unpaid fees, both settling out of court;{{sfn|Burlingame|2012|p=10}} Malcolm and his band performed a year later at the film's premiere in Kingston.{{sfn|Burlingame|2012|p=10}}\n\n== Release and reception ==\n\n=== Promotion ===\nAs soon as late 1961, United Artists started a marketing campaign to make James Bond a well-known name in North America. Newspapers received a box set of Bond's books, as well as a booklet detailing the Bond character and a picture of Ursula Andress.{{sfn|Balio|1987|pp=259\u2013260}} Eon and United Artists made licensing deals revolving around the character's tastes, having merchandising tie-ins with drink, tobacco, men's clothing and car companies. The campaign also focused on Ian Fleming's name due to the minor success of the books.{{sfn|Lindner|2009|pp=120\u2013121}} After ''Dr. No'' had a successful run in Europe, Sean Connery and Terence Young did a cross-country tour in March 1963, which featured screening previews for the film and press conferences. It culminated in a well-publicised premiere in Kingston, where most of the film is set.{{sfn|Balio|1987|pp=259\u2013260}}{{sfn|Lindner|2009|pp=120\u2013121}} Some of the campaign emphasised the sex appeal of the film, with the poster artwork, by [[Mitchell Hooks]], depicting Sean Connery and four scantily clad women.{{cn|date=August 2019}} The campaign also included the 007 logo designed by Joseph Caroff with a pistol as part of the seven.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Selling Bond|url=http://ianfleming.org/mkkbb/magazine/posters.shtml |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050410155944/http://ianfleming.org/mkkbb/magazine/posters.shtml |archivedate=10 April 2005|page=126 |work=[[Cinefantastique]] |volume=37 |issue=9 |date=Winter 2006|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\n''Dr. No'' had its worldwide premiere at the [[London Pavilion]], on 5 October 1962, expanding to the rest of the United Kingdom three days later.{{sfn|Tesche|2002|p=425}} The North American premiere on 8 May 1963 was more low-profile, with 450 cinemas in [[Midwestern United States|Midwest]] and [[Southwestern United States|Southwest]] regions.{{sfn| Chapman |2007|p=253|quote=According to ''[[the Hollywood Reporter]]'' (25 March 1963, p. 3), ''Dr. No'' 'will premiere in the US with a massive 450-theater engagement in the midwest and southwest starting May 8'.}} On 29 May it opened in both Los Angeles and New York City \u2013 in the former as a [[double-bill]] with ''[[The Young and the Brave]]''{{sfn|Tesche|2002|p=425}} and the latter in United Artists' \"Premiere Showcase\" treatment, screening in 84 screens across the city to avoid the costly Broadway cinemas.{{sfn|Balio|1987|pp=259\u2013260}}\n\n=== Critical response ===\nUpon release, ''Dr. No'' received a mixed critical reception. ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' called Bond a \"blithering bounder\" and \"a great big hairy marshmallow\" who \"almost always manages to seem slightly silly\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Cinema: Hairy Marshmallow|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,896851,00.html|newspaper=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=31 May 1963}}</ref> Stanley Kauffmann in ''[[The New Republic]]'' said that he felt the film \"never decides whether it is suspense or suspense-spoof.\" He also did not like Connery, or the Fleming novels.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Anez|first=Nicholas|title=James Bond|journal=Films in Review|date=1 September 1992|volume=43|issue=9|page=310|ref=harv}}</ref> The [[Catholic Church|Vatican]] condemned ''Dr. No'' describing it as \"a dangerous mixture of violence, vulgarity, sadism and sex\",<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/109137216/|title=The Courier-Journal from Louisville, Kentucky|work=The Courier-Journal|location= Louisville|date=18 May 1965|page=16}}</ref> whilst the [[Moscow Kremlin|Kremlin]] said that Bond was the personification of capitalist evil \u2013 both controversies helped increase public awareness of the film and greater cinema attendance.{{sfn|Pfeiffer|Worrall|1998|p=21}} However Leonard Mosely in ''[[The Daily Express]]'' said that \"''Dr No'' is fun all the way, and even the sex is harmless\",<ref>{{cite news|last=Moseley|first=Leonard|title=James Bond flirts with death|newspaper=[[Daily Express]]|location=London|date=5 October 1962|page=4}}</ref> whilst Penelope Gilliatt in ''[[The Observer]]'' said it was \"full of submerged self-parody\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Gilliatt|first=Penelope|title=Getting a laugh out of Bond|newspaper=[[The Observer]]|location=London|date=7 October 1962|page=27}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]''{{'}}s critic called ''Dr. No'' \"crisp and well-tailored\" and \"a neat and gripping thriller.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=James Bond v Dr. No|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|location=London|date=8 October 1962|page=17}}</ref>\n\nIn the years that followed its release, it became more popular. Writing in 1986, [[Danny Peary]] described ''Dr. No'' as a \"cleverly conceived adaption of Ian Fleming's enjoyable spy thriller&nbsp;... Picture has sex, violence, wit, terrific action sequences, and colorful atmosphere&nbsp;... Connery, Andress, and Wiseman all give memorable performances. There's a slow stretch in the middle and Dr. No could use a decent henchman, but otherwise, the film works marvelously.\" Describing ''Dr. No'' as \"a different type of film\", Peary notes that \"Looking back, one can understand why it caused so much excitement.\"{{sfn|Peary|1986|p=127}}\n\nIn 1999, it was ranked 41 on the [[BFI top 100 British films]] list compiled by the [[British Film Institute]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/455170.stm|title=Entertainment: Best 100 British films - full list|last=|first=|date=23 September 1999|website=BBC News|access-date=14 October 2017}}</ref> The 2005 [[American Film Institute]]'s '100 Years' series also recognised the character of James Bond himself in the film as the [[AFI's 100 Years... 100 Heroes and Villains|third greatest film hero]].<ref>{{cite web|title=100 years series: 100 heroes and villains |url=http://connect.afi.com/site/DocServer/handv100.pdf?docID=246 |work=AFI 100 Years Series |publisher=American Film Industry |accessdate=8 June 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/67oI7bsRP?url=http%3A%2F%2Fconnect.afi.com%2Fsite%2FDocServer%2Fhandv100.pdf%3FdocID%3D246 |archivedate=20 May 2012  }}</ref>{{cbignore}} He was also placed at number eleven on a similar list by ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=The 100 Greatest Movie Characters: 11. James Bond|url=http://www.empireonline.com/100-greatest-movie-characters/default.asp?c=11|work=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]|accessdate=8 June 2011}}</ref> ''[[Premiere (magazine)|Premiere]]'' also listed Bond as the fifth greatest movie character of all time.<ref>{{cite web|title=100 Greatest Movie Characters of All Time|url=http://www.filmsite.org/100characters4.html|work=Premiere Magazine|accessdate=8 June 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== Popular reaction ===\nIn the United Kingdom, playing in 168 cinemas, ''Dr. No'' grossed $840,000 in just two weeks and wound up being the fifth most popular movie of the year there.<ref>{{cite news|title=Money-Making Films of 1962|newspaper=[[The Times]]|date=4 January 1964|location=London|page=4}}</ref> The box office results in mainland Europe were also positive.{{sfn|Balio|1987|pp=259\u2013260}} The film ended up grossing $6 million, making it a financial success compared to its $1 million budget.{{sfn|Balio|1987|pp=259\u2013260}}{{sfn|Lindner|2009|pp=120\u2013121}} The original North American [[gross rental]] was $2 million, increasing to $6 million after its first reissue in 1965, as a double feature with ''From Russia with Love''. The following reissue was in 1966 paired with ''[[Goldfinger (film)|Goldfinger]]'', to compensate the fact that [[You Only Live Twice (film)|the next Bond movie]] would only come out in the following year.{{sfn|Balio|1987|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=9EeK5s3aw44C&pg=PA262 262]\u2013265}} The total gross of ''Dr. No'' ended up being $59.6 million worldwide,<ref name=\"the-numbers\">{{cite web|title=Dr No|url=http://www.the-numbers.com/movies/1963/0JB01.php|work=The Numbers|publisher=Nash Information Services, LLC|accessdate=1 June 2009}}</ref> [[IGN]] listed it as sixth-best Bond film ever,<ref>{{cite web|title=James Bond's Top 20 (9\u20136)|url=http://uk.movies.ign.com/articles/746/746573p3.html|work=James Bond's Top 20|publisher=IGN|accessdate=1 June 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927015430/http://uk.movies.ign.com/articles/746/746573p3.html|archivedate=27 September 2011}}</ref> ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' put it at seventh among Bond films,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,1560072_16,00.html|title=Ranking the Bond Films |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|last1=Svetkey |first1=Benjamin |last2=Rich |first2=Joshua |date=1 December 2006|accessdate=1 June 2009}}</ref> and Norman Wilner of [[MSN]] as twelfth best.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://movies.sympatico.msn.ca/features/ArticleNormanWilner.aspx?cp-documentid=436189|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080119210839/http://movies.sympatico.msn.ca/features/ArticleNormanWilner.aspx?cp-documentid=436189|title=Rating the Spy Game|publisher=MSN|author=Wilner, Norman|archivedate=19 January 2008|accessdate=1 June 2009}}</ref> The [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]] sampled 56 reviews and judged 95% of the reviews as positive.<ref name=rt>{{cite web | title=Dr. No | url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/dr_no/ | website=Rotten Tomatoes | accessdate=3 March 2010}}</ref> President John F. Kennedy was a fan of Ian Fleming's novels<ref>{{cite web|title=John F. Kennedy Miscellaneous Information|url=http://www.jfklibrary.org/Research/Ready-Reference/JFK-Miscellaneous-Information.aspx|publisher=John F. Kennedy Presidential Library and Museum|accessdate=7 June 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120221225259/http://www.jfklibrary.org/Research/Ready-Reference/JFK-Miscellaneous-Information.aspx|archivedate=21 February 2012 }}</ref> and requested a private showing of ''Dr. No'' in the White House.<ref name=\"Dodds 2005 266\u2013289\"/>\n\nIn 2003, [[White bikini of Ursula Andress|the scene of Andress emerging from the water in a bikini]] topped [[Channel 4]]'s list of one hundred sexiest scenes of film history.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/3250386.stm |title=Andress scene voted 'most sexy' |date=30 November 2003 |work=[[BBC News]]}}</ref> The bikini was sold in 2001 at an auction for $61,500.<ref>{{cite news|first=Kathryn |last=Westcott |date=5 June 2006| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/in_depth/5130460.stm |title=The bikini: Not a brief affair |work=[[BBC News]]}}</ref> ''Entertainment Weekly'' and [[IGN]] ranked her first in a top ten \"Bond babes\" list.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,1557446_10,00.html |title=Countdown! The 10 best Bond girls |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date = 24 November 2006 | accessdate=24 February 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Zdyrko|first=Dave|title=Top 10 Bond Babes|url=http://uk.stars.ign.com/articles/746/746292p2.html|website=IGN|accessdate=8 June 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== The introduction of James Bond ===\n[[File:Bond, James Bond.webm|thumb|right|A seminal moment in cinema. Sean Connery introduces [[James Bond]] to the film world with his trademark statement, \"Bond, James Bond.\"|alt=Video clip from the film, set in a casino. A woman at the table, wearing a red dress, asks \"Mister ...?\" and a man in a suit answers \"Bond, James Bond\" as he lights his cigarette.]]\nThe character James Bond was introduced towards, but not at, the beginning of the film in a \"now-famous nightclub sequence featuring Sylvia Trench\",{{sfn|Barnes|Hearn|2001|p=11}} to whom he makes his \"immortal introduction\".{{sfn|Pfeiffer|Worrall|1998|p=15}} The introduction to the character in ''Le Cercle at Les Ambassadeurs'', an upmarket gambling club, is derived from Bond's introduction in the first novel, ''[[Casino Royale (novel)|Casino Royale]]'',{{sfn|Chapman|2007|p=58}} which Fleming had used because \"skill at gambling and knowledge of how to behave in a casino were seen&nbsp;... as attributes of a gentleman\".{{sfn|Black|2005|p=7}} After losing a hand of [[Baccarat (card game)|Chemin de Fer]] to Bond, Trench asks his name. There is the \"most important gesture [in]&nbsp;... the way he lights his cigarette before giving her the satisfaction of an answer. 'Bond, James Bond'.\"{{sfn|Comentale|Watt|Willman|2005|p=45}} Once Connery says his line, [[Monty Norman]]'s [[James Bond Theme|Bond theme]] plays \"and creates an indelible link between music and character.\"{{sfn|Lindner|2009|p=142}} In the short scene introducing Bond, there are portrayed \"qualities of strength, action, reaction, violence \u2013 and this elegant, slightly brutal gambler with the quizzical sneer we see before us who answers a woman when he's good and ready.\"{{sfn|Comentale|Watt|Willman|2005|p=45}} [[Raymond Benson]], author of the continuation Bond novels, has stated that as the music fades up on the scene, \"we have ourselves a piece of classic cinema\".{{sfn|Benson|1988|p=170}}\n\nFollowing the release of ''Dr. No'', the quote \"Bond&nbsp;... James Bond\", became a [[catch phrase]] that entered the [[lexicon]] of Western popular culture: writers Cork and Scivally said of the introduction in ''Dr. No'' that the \"signature introduction would become the most famous and loved film line ever\".{{sfn|Cork|Scivally|2002|p=6}} In 2001 it was voted as the \"best-loved one-liner in cinema\" by British cinema goers.<ref>{{cite news|title=James Bond tops motto poll|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/film/1383350.stm|work=BBC News|date=11 June 2001}}</ref> In 2005, it was honoured as the 22nd greatest quotation in cinema history by the [[American Film Institute]] as part of their [[AFI's 100 Years...100 Movie Quotes|100 Years Series]].<ref>{{cite web|title=100 Years Series: \"Movie Quotes\" |url=http://connect.afi.com/site/DocServer/quotes100.pdf?docID=242 |work=AFI 100 Years Series |publisher=American Film Industry |accessdate=8 June 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716070844/http://connect.afi.com/site/DocServer/quotes100.pdf?docID=242 |archivedate=16 July 2011 }}</ref>\n\n== Comic book adaptation ==\n{{Main|Dr. No (comics)}}\nAround the time of ''Dr. No''{{'}}s release in October 1962, a comic book adaptation of the screenplay, written by Norman J. Nodel, was published in the United Kingdom as part of the ''[[Classics Illustrated]]'' anthology series. It was later reprinted in the United States by [[DC Comics]] as part of its ''[[Showcase (comic book)|Showcase]]'' anthology series, in January 1963. This was the first American comic book appearance of James Bond and is noteworthy for being a relatively rare example of a British comic being reprinted in a fairly high-profile American comic. It was also one of the earliest comics to be censored on racial grounds (some skin tones and dialogue were changed for the American market).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newsfromme.com/archives/2006_12_03.html |title=Secrets Behind the Comics |first=Mark |last=Evanier |authorlink=Mark Evanier|publisher=NewsFromme.com |date=3 December 2006 |accessdate=20 July 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120208081002/http://www.newsfromme.com/archives/2006_12_03.html|archivedate=8 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Legacy ==\n{{Quote box|align=right|width=33%|salign=right|It is because of [Ken Adam] that people believe criminal masterminds operate from the insides of dormant volcanoes and travel between their sumptuously decorated lairs on chrome-plated monorails. It's his fault that we think gold bars are stacked in vast cathedral-tall warehouses and that secret agents escape capture by using jetpacks or ejector seats.|-- Johnny Dee, writing in ''[[The Guardian]]'' (2005).<ref name=drill/>}}\n\n''Dr. No'' was the first of 25 ''James Bond'' films produced by Eon, which have grossed just over $5 billion in box office returns alone,<ref>{{cite web|title=Box Office History for James Bond Movies|url=http://www.the-numbers.com/movies/series/JamesBond.php|publisher=Nash Information Services, LLC|accessdate=29 August 2011}}</ref> making the series one of the [[List of highest-grossing film series|highest-grossing ever]]. It is estimated that since ''Dr. No'', a quarter of the world's population have seen at least one ''Bond'' film.<ref name=\"Dodds 2005 266\u2013289\"/> ''Dr. No'' also launched a successful genre of \"secret agent\" films that flourished in the 1960s.{{sfn|Smith|2002|p=21}} The UK Film Distributors' Association have stated that the importance of ''Dr. No'' to the British film industry cannot be overstated, as it, and the subsequent ''Bond'' series of films, \"form the backbone of the industry\".<ref>{{cite news|title=British film classics: Dr. No|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/film/2787017.stm|work=BBC News|date=21 February 2003}}</ref>\n\n''Dr. No'' \u2013 and the ''Bond'' films in general \u2013 also inspired television output, with the [[NBC]] series ''[[The Man from U.N.C.L.E.]]'',<ref>{{cite journal|last=Grigg|first=Richard|title=Vanquishing Evil without the Help of God: The Man from U.N.C.L.E. and a World Come of Age|journal=Journal of Communication & Religion|date=November 2007|volume=30|issue=2|pages=308\u2013339|ref=harv}}</ref> which was described as the \"first network television imitation\" of Bond.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Worland|first=Rick|title=The Man From U.N.C.L.E. and TV espionage in the 1960s|journal=Journal of Popular Film & Television|date=Winter 1994|volume=21|issue=4|pages=150\u2013162|doi=10.1080/01956051.1994.9943983|ref=harv}}</ref>\nThe style of the Bond films, largely derived from production designer Ken Adam, is one of the hallmarks of the Bond film series,<ref name=drill/> and the effect of his work on Dr. No's lair can be seen in another film he worked on, ''[[Dr. Strangelove]]''.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Stillman|first=Grant B.|title=Two of the MADdest scientists: where Strangelove Meets Dr. No; or, unexpected roots for Kubrick's cold war classic|journal=Film History|date=Winter 2008|volume=20|issue=4|pages=487\u2013500|issn=0892-2160|doi=10.2979/FIL.2008.20.4.487|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\nAs the first film in the series, a number of the elements of ''Dr. No'' were contributors to subsequent films, including Monty Norman's \"[[James Bond Theme]]\" and Maurice Binder's gun barrel sequence, variants of which all appeared in subsequent films.<ref name=\"Inside Dr. No documentary\"/> These conventions were also lampooned in spoof films, such as the [[Austin Powers (film series)|''Austin Powers'' series]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Gleiberman|first=Owen|title=A wild and crazy spy|journal=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=9 May 1997|issue=378|page=56|issn=1049-0434|ref=harv}}</ref> The first spoof films happened relatively soon after ''Dr. No'', with the 1964 film ''[[Carry On Spying]]'' showing the villain Dr. Crow being overcome by agents who included Charlie Bind ([[Charles Hawtrey (actor born 1914)|Charles Hawtrey]]) and Daphne Honeybutt ([[Barbara Windsor]]).<ref>{{cite web|last=Angelini|first=Sergio|title=Carry on Spying (1964)|url=http://www.screenonline.org.uk/film/id/466477/|work=[[Screenonline]]|publisher=[[British Film Institute]]|accessdate=3 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nSales of Fleming's novels rose sharply after the release of ''Dr. No'' and the subsequent films. In the seven months after ''Dr. No'' was released, 1.5 million copies of the novel were sold.{{Sfn|Black|2005|p=96 ({{Google books|g4-sFrU8Xw0C|online copy|page=96}})}} Worldwide sales of all the ''Bond'' books rose throughout the 1960s as ''Dr. No'' and the subsequent films \u2013 ''[[From Russia with Love (film)|From Russia with Love]]'' and ''Goldfinger'' \u2013 were released: in 1961 500,000 books had been sold, which rose to six million in 1964 and seven million in 1965. Between the years 1962 to 1967, a total of nearly 22.8 million Bond novels were sold.{{Sfn|Black|2005|p=97 ({{Google books|g4-sFrU8Xw0C|online copy|page=97}})}}\n\nThe film influenced ladies' fashion, with the bikini worn by Ursula Andress proving to be a huge hit: \"not only sent sales of two-piece swimwear skyrocketing, it also made Andress an international celebrity\".{{sfn| Pedersen|2004|p=69}} Andress herself acknowledged that the \"bikini made me into a success. As a result of starring in ''Dr. No'' as the first Bond girl I was given the freedom to take my pick of future roles and to become financially independent\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Bennett|first=Will|title=Former Bond girl to sell Dr. No bikini|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1314376/Former-Bond-girl-to-sell-Dr-No-bikini.html|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|location=London|date=12 January 2001}}</ref> It has been claimed that the use of the swimwear in ''Dr. No'' led to \"the biggest impact on the history of the bikini\".{{sfn| Pedersen|2004|p=69}}\n\n=== Global James Bond Day ===\nOn 5 October 2012, fifty years after the release of the film, Eon Productions celebrated \"Global James Bond Day\", a series of events around the world.<ref>{{cite web|title=Eon Announces a Global James Bond Day on October 5th This Year|url=http://www.firstshowing.net/2012/eon-announces-a-global-james-bond-day-on-october-5th-this-year/|publisher=First Showing|accessdate=23 April 2013}}</ref> Events included a film festival of showings of the ''James Bond'' films, a documentary of the series, an online auction for charity and further events at the [[Museum of Modern Art]] and the [[Toronto International Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Global James Bond Day to celebrate 007's 50th anniversary|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/jamesbond/9509677/Global-James-Bond-Day-to-celebrate-007s-50th-anniversary.html|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]}}</ref> A concert of various music was held in Los Angeles in conjunction with the New York event.<ref>{{cite web|title=Global James Bond Day: The world celebrates 007 |url=http://www.cleveland.com/moviebuff/index.ssf/2012/10/global_james_bond_day_the_worl.html|work=The Plain Dealer|accessdate=23 April 2013}}</ref>  The day also saw the release of \"[[Skyfall (Adele song)|Skyfall]]\", the theme song of the 2012 ''[[James Bond in film|James Bond]]'' film [[Skyfall|of the same name]]; the song was released at 0:07 [[British Summer Time|BST]].<ref name=press>{{cite web|url=http://www.007.com/skyfall-official-theme-song-news/|title=Skyfall Official Theme Song News: Release To Coincide With Bond's 50th Anniversary|publisher=[[Eon Productions]]|date=1 October 2012|accessdate=1 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Outline of James Bond]]\n{{Portalbar|1960s|Film|United Kingdom}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Sources ==\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n\n* {{Cite book|last=Balio|first=Tino|title=United Artists: The Company That Changed the Film Industry|publisher=University of Wisconsin Press|year=1987|isbn=978-0-299-11440-4|ref=harv|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/unitedartistscom00bali}}\n* {{Cite book |last1=Barnes |first1=Alan |last2=Hearn |first2=Marcus |year=2001 |title=Kiss Kiss Bang! Bang!: the Unofficial James Bond Film Companion|publisher=Batsford Books|isbn=978-0-7134-8182-2|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Benson|first=Raymond|authorlink=Raymond Benson|title=[[The James Bond Bedside Companion]]|year=1988|publisher=Boxtree Ltd|location=London|isbn=978-1-85283-233-9|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Black|first=Jeremy|title=The politics of James Bond: from Fleming's novel to the big screen|year=2005|publisher=University of Nebraska Press|isbn=978-0-8032-6240-9|ref=harv|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/politicsofjamesb0000blac}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Bray|first=Christopher|title=Sean Connery; The measure of a Man|year=2010|publisher=Faber and Faber|location=London|isbn=978-0-571-23807-1 |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Broccoli|first=Albert R|authorlink=Albert R. Broccoli|title=When the Snow Melts|year=1998|publisher=Boxtree|location=London|isbn=978-0-7522-1162-6 |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |last= Burlingame |first= Jon |title= The Music of James Bond |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=yv_yExgGOccC&lpg=PP