ope]]\n[[Category:Landlocked countries]]\n[[Category:Member states of NATO]]\n[[Category:Member states of the Council of Europe]]\n[[Category:Member states of the European Union]]\n[[Category:Member states of the Union for the Mediterranean]]\n[[Category:Member states of the United Nations]]\n[[Category:Republics]]\n[[Category:Slovak-speaking countries and territories]]\n[[Category:States and territories established in 1993]]\n", "name_user": "Oliszydlowski", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCulture:moved image to avoid clutter", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slovakia"}
{"title_page": "Mystery Sea Raider", "text_new": "{{short description|1940 film}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Mystery Sea Raider\n| image\t         = Mystery Sea Raider FilmPoster.jpeg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Edward Dmytryk]]\n| producer       = Eugene J. Zukor\n| screenplay     = [[Edward E. Paramore Jr.]]\n| story          = Robert Grant\n| starring       = [[Carole Landis]]<br>[[Henry Wilcoxon]]<br>[[Onslow Stevens]] \n| music          = \n| cinematography = [[Harry Fischbeck]]\n| editing        = Archie Marshek\n| studio         = Paramount Pictures\n| distributor    = [[Paramount Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1940|8|9}}\n| runtime        = 76 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n}}\n\n'''''Mystery Sea Raider''''' is a 1940 American [[drama film|drama]] [[war film]] directed by [[Edward Dmytryk]] and starring [[Carole Landis]], [[Henry Wilcoxon]] and [[Onslow Stevens]].<ref name=\"NY Times\">{{cite web |url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/103537/Mystery-Sea-Raider/overview |title=Mystery Sea Raider |accessdate=May 1, 2011 |work=NY Times}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nA woman ([[Carole Landis]]) and a U.S. captain ([[Henry Wilcoxon]]) foil a German spy's ([[Onslow Stevens]]) plan to use their freighter to sink a British ship.\n==Cast==\n* [[Carole Landis]] as June McCarthy\n* [[Henry Wilcoxon]] as Captain Jimmy Madden\n* [[Onslow Stevens]] as Carl Cutler\n* [[Kathleen Howard]] as Maggie Clancy\n* Wally Rairden as Blake, 3rd Mate (as Wallace Rairdon)\n* [[Sven Hugo Borg]] as Sven\n* [[Henry Victor]] as Cmdr. Bulow\n* [[Roland Varno]] as Lt. Schmidt\n* [[Louis Adlon]] as Lerner\n* Willy Kaufman as Lt. Felder\n* [[Monte Blue]] as Captain Norberg\n* [[Matthew Boulton (actor)|Matthew Boulton]] as Captain Howard\n* Gohr Van Vleck as Captain Van Wyck\n* [[Jean Del Val]] as Captain Benoit\n* [[Kay Linaker]] as Flossie La Mare\n* [[Reed Howes]] as Hughes, Carl's Chauffeur\n* Phil Warren as Sparks, Radio Operator (as Philip Wareen)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0032834|Mystery Sea Raider}}\n\n{{Edward Dmytryk}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mystery Sea Raider}}\n[[Category:1940 films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American war drama films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:1940s war drama films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Edward Dmytryk]]\n{{1940s-drama-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1940 film}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Mystery Sea Raider\n| image\t         = Mystery Sea Raider FilmPoster.jpeg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Edward Dmytryk]]\n| producer       = Eugene J. Zukor\n| screenplay     = [[Edward E. Paramore Jr.]]\n| story          = Robert Grant\n| starring       = [[Carole Landis]]<br>[[Henry Wilcoxon]]<br>[[Onslow Stevens]] \n| music          = \n| cinematography = [[Harry Fischbeck]]\n| editing        = Archie Marshek\n| studio         = Paramount Pictures\n| distributor    = [[Paramount Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1940|8|9}}\n| runtime        = 76 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n}}\n\n'''''Mystery Sea Raider''''' is a 1940 American [[drama film|drama]] [[war film]] directed by [[Edward Dmytryk]] and starring [[Carole Landis]], [[Henry Wilcoxon]] and [[Onslow Stevens]].<ref name=\"NY Times\">{{cite web |url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/103537/Mystery-Sea-Raider/overview |title=Mystery Sea Raider |accessdate=May 1, 2011 |work=NY Times}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nA woman ([[Carole Landis]]) and a U.S. captain ([[Henry Wilcoxon]]) foil a German spy's ([[Onslow Stevens]]) plan to use their freighter to sink a British ship.\n==Cast==\n* [[Carole Landis]] as June McCarthy\n* [[Henry Wilcoxon]] as Captain Jimmy Madden\n* [[Onslow Stevens]] as Carl Cutler\n* [[Kathleen Howard]] as Maggie Clancy\n* Wally Rairden as Blake, 3rd Mate (as Wallace Rairdon)\n* [[Sven Hugo Borg]] as Sven\n* [[Henry Victor]] as Cmdr. Bulow\n* [[Roland Varno]] as Lt. Schmidt\n* [[Louis Adlon]] as Lerner\n* Willy Kaufman as Lt. Felder\n* [[Monte Blue]] as Captain Norberg\n* [[Matthew Boulton (actor)|Matthew Boulton]] as Captain Howard\n* Gohr Van Vleck as Captain Van Wyck\n* [[Jean Del Val]] as Captain Benoit\n* [[Kay Linaker]] as Flossie La Mare\n* [[Reed Howes]] as Hughes, Carl's Chauffeur\n* Phil Warren as Sparks, Radio Operator (as Philip Wareen)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0032834|Mystery Sea Raider}}\n\n{{Edward Dmytryk}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mystery Sea Raider}}\n[[Category:1940 films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American war drama films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:1940s war drama films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Edward Dmytryk]]\n{{1940s-drama-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mystery_Sea_Raider"}
{"title_page": "Idit Zehavi", "text_new": "{{short description|Israeli astrophysicist}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Idit Zehavi\n| image         = <!-- just the filename, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by the blind and visually impaired's speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software  -->\n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| native_name        = \u05e2\u05d3\u05d9\u05ea \u05d6\u05d4\u05d1\u05d9\n| native_name_lang   = he\n| birth_date    = {{Birth year and age|1969}}\n| birth_place   = [[Israel]]\n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = Israeli\n| alma mater    = [[Hebrew University of Jerusalem]]<br/>[[University of Chicago]]\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = astrophysicist, astronomer\n| employer      = [[Fermi National Accelerator Laboratory]]<br/>[[University of Arizona]]<br/>[[Case Western Reserve University]]\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n'''Idit Zehavi''' ({{lang-he|\u05e2\u05d3\u05d9\u05ea \u05d6\u05d4\u05d1\u05d9}}) (born 1969) is an Israeli [[astrophysicist]] and researcher who discovered an anomaly in the mapping of the cosmos, which offered insight into how the universe is expanding. She is part of the team completing the [[Sloan Digital Sky Survey]] and is one of the world's most highly cited scientists according to the list published annually by Thomson [[Reuters]].\n\n== Biography ==\nIdit Zehavi was born in Israel in 1969<ref name=\"hired  and birth\">{{cite news|title=Brain Gain: Idit Zehavi|url=http://www.cleveland.com/businessmonday/wide/index.ssf?/businessmonday/wide/11braingain27.html|access-date=20 November 2015|publisher=[[The Plain Dealer]]|date=27 November 2006|location=Cleveland, Ohio|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151121045153/http://www.cleveland.com/businessmonday/wide/index.ssf?%2Fbusinessmonday%2Fwide%2F11braingain27.html|archive-date=21 November 2015|df=}}</ref> and completed her education in [[Jerusalem]], earning a PhD from the [[The Racah Institute of Physics|Racah Institute of Physics]] at the [[Hebrew University of Jerusalem]] in 1998.<ref name=\"The Hebrew University of Jerusalem\">{{cite web|title=Cosmology Group|url=http://www.phys.huji.ac.il/~dekel/group.html|publisher=The Hebrew University of Jerusalem|accessdate=20 November 2015|location=Jerusalem, Israel}}</ref> That same year, while researching the expansion of the universe, she and a colleague, Avishai Dekel, noted an anomaly in the cosmos which suggested that the portion of the galaxy where earth lies  is expanding faster than the entirety of the universe. The findings were independently noted by another researcher, Adam Riess, from the [[University of California, Berkeley]].<ref name=expansion>{{cite news|title=Supernovas Light Up Cosmic Growth Spurt|url=http://news.sciencemag.org/1998/05/supernovas-light-cosmic-growth-spurt|accessdate=20 November 2015|publisher=Science Magazine|date=15 May 1998|location=American Association for the Advancement of Science}}</ref> Soon after, Zehavi moved to the United States to complete her post-doctorate studies in [[galaxy clustering]] at the [[University of Chicago]] and participate in research at the [[Fermi National Accelerator Laboratory]].<ref name=FermiNews>{{cite journal|last1=Perricone|first1=Mike|title=Friends of Friends|journal=FermiNews|date=21 March 2003|volume=26|issue=5|url=https://www.fnal.gov/pub/ferminews/ferminews03-03-21/p1.html|accessdate=20 November 2015|publisher=[[Fermilab]]|location=Batavia, Illinois}}</ref> She left Fermilab in 2004 for the [[University of Arizona]] and continued working on the research of the [[Sloan Digital Sky Survey]] (SDSS).<ref name=\"Sloan Sky Survey\">{{cite news|title=Astronomers Find Gravity's Signature in Galaxy Distribution|url=http://uanews.org/story/astronomers-find-gravity-s-signature-in-galaxy-distribution|accessdate=20 November 2015|publisher=UA News|date=14 January 2005|location=University of Arizona, Tucson, Arizona}}</ref> In 2005, she participated in research under the direction of Daniel Eisenstein, which detected \"cosmic ripples\",<ref name=ripples>{{cite news|title=SDSS Measures Size of the Universe; Finds Big Bang Echo in Galaxy Distribution|url=http://www.fnal.gov/pub/today/archive/archive_2005/today05-04-07.html|accessdate=20 November 2015|publisher=Fermilab Today|date=7 April 2005|location=Batavia, Illinois}}</ref> which confirmed the cosmological theory of the creation of the universe.<ref name=\"big bang confirmed\">{{cite journal|title=Detection of the Baryon Acoustic Peak in the Large-Scale Correlation Function of SDSS Luminous Red Galaxies|arxiv=astro-ph/0501171|date=10 Jan 2005|author1=D. J. Eisenstein |author2=I. Zehavi |author3=D. W. Hogg |author4=R. Scoccimarro |author5=M. R. Blanton |author6=R. C. Nichol |author7=R. Scranton |author8=H. Seo |author9=M. Tegmark |author10=Z. Zheng |author11=S. Anderson |author12=J. Annis |author13=N. Bahcall |author14=J. Brinkmann |author15=S. Burles |author16=F. J. Castander |author17=A. Connolly |author18=I. Csabai |author19=M. Doi |author20=M. Fukugita |author21=J. A. Frieman |author22=K. Glazebrook |author23=J. E. Gunn |author24=J. S. Hendry |author25=G. Hennessy |author26=Z. Ivezic |author27=S. Kent |author28=G. R. Knapp |author29=H. Lin |author30=Y. Loh |author31=R. H. Lupton |author32=B. Margon |author33=T. McKay |author34=A. Meiksin |author35=J. A. Munn |author36=A. Pope |author37=M. Richmond |author38=D. Schlegel |author39=D. Schneider |author40=K. Shimasaku |author41=C. Stoughton |author42=M. Strauss |author43=M. SubbaRao |author44=A. S. Szalay |author45=I. Szapudi |author46=D. Tucker |author47=B. Yanny |author48=D. York |doi=10.1086/466512 |volume=633 |journal=The Astrophysical Journal |pages=560\u2013574 |bibcode=2005ApJ...633..560E}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, she joined [[Case Western Reserve University]] of [[Cleveland, Ohio]], as an Associate Professor in the Astronomy Department.<ref name=\"hired  and birth\" /><ref name=professor>{{cite web|title=Idit Zehavi|url=http://artsci.case.edu/faculty/idit-zehavi/|publisher=[[Case Western Reserve University]]|accessdate=20 November 2015|location=Cleveland, Ohio}}</ref> In 2009, Zehavi was awarded a grant from the U.S. [[National Science Foundation]] to continue her work with the SDSS to expand her work on galaxy clustering to encompass a larger scale view of the universe.<ref name=\"National Science Foudation\">{{cite web|title=From Galaxy Clustering to Galaxy Formation and Evolution|url=http://grantome.com/grant/NSF/AST-0907947|publisher=Grantome|accessdate=20 November 2015}}</ref> According to the annual listing produced by Thomson [[Reuters]], Zehavi is one of the world's most highly cited scientists.<ref name=\"highy cited\">{{cite web|title=The World's Most Influential Scientific Minds|url=http://sites.biology.duke.edu/donglab/images/papers/thomas_reuter_2014.pdf|publisher=[[Thomson Reuters]]|access-date=20 November 2015|date=2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117020628/http://sites.biology.duke.edu/donglab/images/papers/thomas_reuter_2014.pdf|archive-date=17 November 2015|df=}}</ref>\n\n== Selected works ==\n*{{cite journal |last=Zaroubi|first=Saleem |last2=Zehavi|first2=Idit|last3=Dekel|first3=Avishai  |display-authors=etal |date=September 1997|title=Large\u2010Scale Power Spectrum from Peculiar Velocities via Likelihood Analysis|url= |journal=The Astrophysical Journal |volume=486|issue=1|pages=21\u201331|doi= 10.1086/304481|arxiv = astro-ph/9610226 |bibcode = 1997ApJ...486...21Z }}\n*{{cite journal |last=Zehavi|first=Idit |last2=Riess|first2=Adam G |last3=Kirshner|first3=Robert P |last4=Dekel|first4=Avishai |date=1998|title=A Local Hubble Bubble from Type 1a Supernovae|url= |journal=The Astrophysical Journal |volume=503|issue=2|page=483|doi=  10.1086/306015|arxiv = astro-ph/9802252 |bibcode = 1998ApJ...503..483Z }}\n*{{cite journal |last=Zehavi|first=Idit |last2=Blanton|first2=Michael R |last3=Frieman|first3=Joshua A |display-authors=etal |date=2002|title=Galaxy Clustering in Early Sloan Digital Sky Survey Redshift Data|url= |journal=The Astrophysical Journal|volume=571|issue=1|page=172|doi=  10.1086/339893|arxiv = astro-ph/0106476 |bibcode = 2002ApJ...571..172Z }}\n*{{cite journal |last=Zehavi|first=Idit |last2=Zheng|first2=Zheng |last3=Weinberg|first3=David H |display-authors=etal |date=2002|title=The Luminosity and Color Dependence of the Galaxy Correlation Function|url= |journal=The Astrophysical Journal|volume=630|issue=1|page=1|doi=10.1086/431891|arxiv=astro-ph/0408569v2 |bibcode=2005ApJ...630....1Z}}\n*{{cite journal |last=Zehavi|first=Idit |last2=Eisenstein|first2=Daniel J |last3=Nichol|first3=Robert C |display-authors=etal |date=2005|title=The Intermediate-Scale Clustering of Luminous Red Galaxies|url= |journal=The Astrophysical Journal|volume=621|issue=1|page=22|doi=  10.1086/427495|arxiv = astro-ph/0411557 |bibcode = 2005ApJ...621...22Z }}\n*{{cite journal|last1=Eisenstein|first1=Daniel J |last2=Zehavi|first2=Idit |last3=Hogg|first3=David W |display-authors=etal |date=October\u2013November 2005|title=Detection of the Baryon Acoustic Peak in the Large\u2010Scale Correlation Function of SDSS Luminous Red Galaxies|url= |journal=The Astrophysical Journal|volume=633|issue=2|pages=560\u2013574|doi=  10.1086/466512|arxiv = astro-ph/0501171 |bibcode = 2005ApJ...633..560E }}\n*{{cite journal |last=Sheth|first=Ravi K |last2=Zehavi|first2=Idit|date=April 2009|title=Linear theory and velocity correlations of clusters|url= |journal=Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society |volume=394|issue=3|pages=1459\u20131462|doi=  10.1111/j.1365-2966.2008.14326.x|arxiv = 0812.1037 |bibcode = 2009MNRAS.394.1459S }}\n*{{cite journal|last1=Guo|first1=Hong |last2=Zehavi|first2=Idit |last3=Zheng|first3=Zheng |date=September\u2013October 2012|title=A New Method to Correct for Fiber Collisions in Galaxy Two-Point Statistics|url= |journal=The Astrophysical Journal |volume=756|issue=2|page=127|doi=  10.1088/0004-637X/756/2/127|arxiv = 1111.6598 |bibcode = 2012ApJ...756..127G }}\n*{{cite journal|last1=Guo|first1=Hong |last2=Zehavi|first2=Idit |last3=Zheng|first3=Zheng |display-authors=etal |date=December 2012|title=The clustering of galaxies in the SDSS-III Baryon Oscillation Spectroscopic Survey: Luminosity and Color Dependence and Redshift Evolution|url= |journal=The Astrophysical Journal| volume=767|issue=2|page=122|doi=10.1088/0004-637X/767/2/122|arxiv = 1212.1211 |bibcode = 2013ApJ...767..122G }}\n*{{cite journal|last1=Guo|first1=Hong |last2=Zheng|first2=Zheng|last3=Zehavi|first3=Idit |display-authors=etal |date=January 2014|title=The clustering of galaxies in the SDSS-III Baryon Oscillation Spectroscopic Survey: modeling of the luminosity and colour dependence in the Data Release 10|url= |journal=Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society|volume=441|issue=3|pages=2398\u20132413|doi=10.1093/mnras/stu763|arxiv = 1401.3009 |bibcode = 2014MNRAS.441.2398G }}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://www.worldcat.org/search?q=zehavi%2C+idit&fq=ap%3A%22zehavi+idit%22&dblist=638&qt=sort&se=yr&sd=asc&qt=sort_yr_asc WorldCat Publications]\n*{{ResearchGate|Idit_Zehavi}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zehavi, Idit}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Israeli women scientists]]\n[[Category:Israeli astronomers]]\n[[Category:Women astronomers]]\n[[Category:Hebrew University of Jerusalem alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century women scientists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Israeli astrophysicist}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Idit Zehavi\n| image         = <!-- just the filename, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by the blind and visually impaired's speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software  -->\n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| native_name        = \u05e2\u05d3\u05d9\u05ea \u05d6\u05d4\u05d1\u05d9\n| native_name_lang   = he\n| birth_date    = {{Birth year and age|1969}}\n| birth_place   = [[Israel]]\n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = Israeli\n| alma mater    = [[Hebrew University of Jerusalem]]<br/>[[University of Chicago]]\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = astrophysicist, astronomer\n| employer      = [[Fermi National Accelerator Laboratory]]<br/>[[University of Arizona]]<br/>[[Case Western Reserve University]]\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n'''Idit Zehavi''' ({{lang-he|\u05e2\u05d3\u05d9\u05ea \u05d6\u05d4\u05d1\u05d9}}) (born 1969) is an Israeli [[astrophysicist]] and researcher who discovered an anomaly in the mapping of the cosmos, which offered insight into how the universe is expanding. She is part of the team completing the [[Sloan Digital Sky Survey]] and is one of the world's most highly cited scientists according to the list published annually by Thomson [[Reuters]].\n\n== Biography ==\nIdit Zehavi was born in Israel in 1969<ref name=\"hired  and birth\">{{cite news|title=Brain Gain: Idit Zehavi|url=http://www.cleveland.com/businessmonday/wide/index.ssf?/businessmonday/wide/11braingain27.html|access-date=20 November 2015|publisher=[[The Plain Dealer]]|date=27 November 2006|location=Cleveland, Ohio|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151121045153/http://www.cleveland.com/businessmonday/wide/index.ssf?%2Fbusinessmonday%2Fwide%2F11braingain27.html|archive-date=21 November 2015|df=}}</ref> and completed her education in [[Jerusalem]], earning a PhD from the [[The Racah Institute of Physics|Racah Institute of Physics]] at the [[Hebrew University of Jerusalem]] in 1998.<ref name=\"The Hebrew University of Jerusalem\">{{cite web|title=Cosmology Group|url=http://www.phys.huji.ac.il/~dekel/group.html|publisher=The Hebrew University of Jerusalem|accessdate=20 November 2015|location=Jerusalem, Israel}}</ref> That same year, while researching the expansion of the universe, she and a colleague, Avishai Dekel, noted an anomaly in the cosmos which suggested that the portion of the galaxy where earth lies  is expanding faster than the entirety of the universe. The findings were independently noted by another researcher, Adam Riess, from the [[University of California, Berkeley]].<ref name=expansion>{{cite news|title=Supernovas Light Up Cosmic Growth Spurt|url=http://news.sciencemag.org/1998/05/supernovas-light-cosmic-growth-spurt|accessdate=20 November 2015|publisher=Science Magazine|date=15 May 1998|location=American Association for the Advancement of Science}}</ref> Soon after, Zehavi moved to the United States to complete her post-doctorate studies in [[galaxy clustering]] at the [[University of Chicago]] and participate in research at the [[Fermi National Accelerator Laboratory]].<ref name=FermiNews>{{cite journal|last1=Perricone|first1=Mike|title=Friends of Friends|journal=FermiNews|date=21 March 2003|volume=26|issue=5|url=https://www.fnal.gov/pub/ferminews/ferminews03-03-21/p1.html|accessdate=20 November 2015|publisher=[[Fermilab]]|location=Batavia, Illinois}}</ref> She left Fermilab in 2004 for the [[University of Arizona]] and continued working on the research of the [[Sloan Digital Sky Survey]] (SDSS).<ref name=\"Sloan Sky Survey\">{{cite news|title=Astronomers Find Gravity's Signature in Galaxy Distribution|url=http://uanews.org/story/astronomers-find-gravity-s-signature-in-galaxy-distribution|accessdate=20 November 2015|publisher=UA News|date=14 January 2005|location=University of Arizona, Tucson, Arizona}}</ref> In 2005, she participated in research under the direction of Daniel Eisenstein, which detected \"cosmic ripples\",<ref name=ripples>{{cite news|title=SDSS Measures Size of the Universe; Finds Big Bang Echo in Galaxy Distribution|url=http://www.fnal.gov/pub/today/archive/archive_2005/today05-04-07.html|accessdate=20 November 2015|publisher=Fermilab Today|date=7 April 2005|location=Batavia, Illinois}}</ref> which confirmed the cosmological theory of the creation of the universe.<ref name=\"big bang confirmed\">{{cite journal|title=Detection of the Baryon Acoustic Peak in the Large-Scale Correlation Function of SDSS Luminous Red Galaxies|arxiv=astro-ph/0501171|date=10 Jan 2005|author1=D. J. Eisenstein |author2=I. Zehavi |author3=D. W. Hogg |author4=R. Scoccimarro |author5=M. R. Blanton |author6=R. C. Nichol |author7=R. Scranton |author8=H. Seo |author9=M. Tegmark |author10=Z. Zheng |author11=S. Anderson |author12=J. Annis |author13=N. Bahcall |author14=J. Brinkmann |author15=S. Burles |author16=F. J. Castander |author17=A. Connolly |author18=I. Csabai |author19=M. Doi |author20=M. Fukugita |author21=J. A. Frieman |author22=K. Glazebrook |author23=J. E. Gunn |author24=J. S. Hendry |author25=G. Hennessy |author26=Z. Ivezic |author27=S. Kent |author28=G. R. Knapp |author29=H. Lin |author30=Y. Loh |author31=R. H. Lupton |author32=B. Margon |author33=T. McKay |author34=A. Meiksin |author35=J. A. Munn |author36=A. Pope |author37=M. Richmond |author38=D. Schlegel |author39=D. Schneider |author40=K. Shimasaku |author41=C. Stoughton |author42=M. Strauss |author43=M. SubbaRao |author44=A. S. Szalay |author45=I. Szapudi |author46=D. Tucker |author47=B. Yanny |author48=D. York |doi=10.1086/466512 |volume=633 |journal=The Astrophysical Journal |pages=560\u2013574 |bibcode=2005ApJ...633..560E}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, she joined [[Case Western Reserve University]] of [[Cleveland, Ohio]], as an Associate Professor in the Astronomy Department.<ref name=\"hired  and birth\" /><ref name=professor>{{cite web|title=Idit Zehavi|url=http://artsci.case.edu/faculty/idit-zehavi/|publisher=[[Case Western Reserve University]]|accessdate=20 November 2015|location=Cleveland, Ohio}}</ref> In 2009, Zehavi was awarded a grant from the U.S. [[National Science Foundation]] to continue her work with the SDSS to expand her work on galaxy clustering to encompass a larger scale view of the universe.<ref name=\"National Science Foudation\">{{cite web|title=From Galaxy Clustering to Galaxy Formation and Evolution|url=http://grantome.com/grant/NSF/AST-0907947|publisher=Grantome|accessdate=20 November 2015}}</ref> According to the annual listing produced by Thomson [[Reuters]], Zehavi is one of the world's most highly cited scientists.<ref name=\"highy cited\">{{cite web|title=The World's Most Influential Scientific Minds|url=http://sites.biology.duke.edu/donglab/images/papers/thomas_reuter_2014.pdf|publisher=[[Thomson Reuters]]|access-date=20 November 2015|date=2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117020628/http://sites.biology.duke.edu/donglab/images/papers/thomas_reuter_2014.pdf|archive-date=17 November 2015|df=}}</ref>\n\n== Selected works ==\n*{{cite journal |last=Zaroubi|first=Saleem |last2=Zehavi|first2=Idit|last3=Dekel|first3=Avishai  |display-authors=etal |date=September 1997|title=Large\u2010Scale Power Spectrum from Peculiar Velocities via Likelihood Analysis|url= |journal=The Astrophysical Journal |volume=486|issue=1|pages=21\u201331|doi= 10.1086/304481|arxiv = astro-ph/9610226 |bibcode = 1997ApJ...486...21Z }}\n*{{cite journal |last=Zehavi|first=Idit |last2=Riess|first2=Adam G |last3=Kirshner|first3=Robert P |last4=Dekel|first4=Avishai |date=1998|title=A Local Hubble Bubble from Type 1a Supernovae|url= |journal=The Astrophysical Journal |volume=503|issue=2|page=483|doi=  10.1086/306015|arxiv = astro-ph/9802252 |bibcode = 1998ApJ...503..483Z }}\n*{{cite journal |last=Zehavi|first=Idit |last2=Blanton|first2=Michael R |last3=Frieman|first3=Joshua A |display-authors=etal |date=2002|title=Galaxy Clustering in Early Sloan Digital Sky Survey Redshift Data|url= |journal=The Astrophysi